<HEAD>China Acts To Reassert Controls Over Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The official press reported Thursday that the government is taking new steps to re-establish order in an economy reeling from speculation and profiteering in scarce materials and widespread tax evasion. The steps include measures to reassert controls over the distribution and pricing of raw materials such as coal and steel, the reports said. The state will also begin a campaign against what it says is rampant tax evasion among <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 14.5 million privately owned enterprises, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Xie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mingan </PERSON>, an official of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, said the state will tighten controls on prices of some raw materials such as coal, rolled steel and non-ferrous metals. He said redundant middlemen will be eliminated, illegal dealers and officials trading power for money will be disciplined and state supplies of materials to production enterprises will be maintained. One aspect of the economic reforms _ decentralization of controls over raw materials _ has led to hoarding, speculation and price-gouging. Middlemen, often with links to influential party and government officials, buy up scarce materials at low government-set prices and sell them for huge profits on free markets. <PERSON> Jin </PERSON> <PERSON> Xin </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, told a conference Wednesday that if the problem of tax evasion among private businessmen goes unsolved, `` it will certainly sap the morale of the dominant working classes and bring adverse effects on the enthusiasm of intellectuals.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s conservative leadership has singled out private entrepreneurs as an example of unhealthy disparities in income levels. Many private businessmen, some operating from simple street stalls, earn more in a day than a worker or teacher makes in a month. A young worker earns about $ 27 a month. <PERSON> Jin </PERSON> said the state was not trying to add to the financial burdens of private businessmen, who have been a stimulus in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic growth over the past decade. He also promised no change in the preferential terms on taxation for foreign investors in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s parliament, was also told Wednesday that more than 2,800 companies lost their business licenses and nearly 800 party and government officials were punished after the government began a drive against shady business practices in October The moves come against the backdrop of a return to Marxist orthodoxy in the political sphere following the military crackdown on the pro-democracy movement in June and a general reassessment of the pace of the nation's market-oriented economic reforms.
</TEXT>
