<HEAD>Tropical Storm Gabrielle Forms Off Cape Verde</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> formed late Wednesday off the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> coast with top winds of 40 mph, becoming the seventh named storm of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, forecasters said. At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> was near latitude 11.0 north and longitude 25.8 west, or about 435 miles southwest of the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The storm, heading west at 20 mph, was expected to strengthen over the next day, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. The storm formed less than a day after its predecessor, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>, dwindled to a tropical depression. It carried winds of 30 mph Wednesday night and was centered about 920 miles south of the westernmost <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> in the north <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. A depression becomes a tropical storm when its winds reach 39 mph. A tropical storm becomes a hurricane once its winds hit 74 mph. There have been three hurricanes so far during the hurricane season, which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
