<HEAD>Funeral Service For Slain Man, TV Crew Attacked In Aftermath of Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto PX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Funeral services were held Wednesday for a black man whose shooting death by police sparked two days of rioting and looting in <LOCATION> Vineland </LOCATION> while a special panel convened on how to calm racial tensions. Community leaders had hoped the unrest following the Sunday night shooting had subsided, but four people were arrested Wednesday, including a man who scuffled with a television news crew, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Tofanelli </PERSON>, a city spokesman. The WPVI-TV news crew from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> was attacked by a group of youths as they interviewed people in downtown <LOCATION> Vineland </LOCATION>, where rioting and looting broke out Monday night, <PERSON> Tofanelli </PERSON> said. News reporter <PERSON> Dann </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> was listed in stable condition at <ORGANIZATION> Newcomb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vineland </LOCATION> with a broken nose and facial injuries, hospital officials said. A cameraman and sound technician were treated for minor injuries and discharged. `` I feel no animosity toward those youngsters out there,'' <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in a telehone interview. `` There is a lot of frustration ... a lot of anger here.'' <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s wallet and some television equipment were stolen. The equipment was returned later, <PERSON> Tofanelli </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, 23, was arrested on assault and robbery charges, <PERSON> Tofanelli </PERSON> said, and three other people were arrested in a separate incident when they disobeyed police orders to leave the area. The charges were not available. About 200 people packed into <ORGANIZATION> Truth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newfield </LOCATION> for a two-hour ceremony in remembrance of 26-year-old <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who was shot and killed by <LOCATION> Vineland </LOCATION> police on Sunday. Mayor <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> met with community leaders and announced the formation of an eight-member special task force to find ways of restoring calm to the city. `` We're hoping this will be the first step,'' <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> said at an informal press conference at his City Hall office. `` We're hoping that we can be assured there wo n't be any more outbreaks.'' <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, president of the local chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People, thought the unrest would end with the memorial service. `` They're grieving, but I do n't think it's going to be a destructive type of thing,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. Mourners gathered outside the small white church in <LOCATION> Newfield </LOCATION>, about several miles north of <LOCATION> Vineland </LOCATION>, as the coffee-colored casket containing <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' body was led to a black hearse. They raised clenched fists in a symbol of black power as a choir sang `` Oh How I Love Jesus.'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' body was taken to a funeral home and then to the state medical examiner's office in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> for a second autopsy. An initial autopsy was performed Monday by the county coroner. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a father of two children, was shot after he allegedly threatened officer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Letizia </PERSON> with a steel rod, said police Chief <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassisi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who was wanted on drug and weapons charges, was spotted by officers after police received an anonymous telephone call about a man on a bicycle carrying drugs, <PERSON> Cassisi </PERSON> said. After being told he was under arrest, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> picked up the rod and approached <PERSON> Letizia </PERSON>, swinging, <PERSON> Cassisi </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Letizia </PERSON>, who is white, fired two shots at <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, hitting him both times, the police chief said. <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Letizia </PERSON> has been taken off street duty and put on special assignment. The mayor said he did not plan to follow the demands of some blacks who want <PERSON> Letizia </PERSON> suspended without pay pending the outcome of an investigation by the state Attorney General's office. <PERSON> Curley </PERSON> said the task force would review the police department's relationship with the mostly minority community as well as the handling of citizen complaints He said a report was expected in about 30 days.
