<HEAD>Record Killing Pace Surpasses 300 in Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Killings in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, continuing at a record pace that police say is largely driven by a burgeoning drug trade, has passed the 300 mark for the year. The city's 300th homicide victim, recorded early Tuesday, was a suburban <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> man gunned down in a northwest <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> drug market, police said. At least 10 people were shot or stabbed in the city Tuesday, police said, and three died. One woman was seriously injured by a stray bullet as she stood outside her northest <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> home. The deaths bring the district's 1989 homicide count to 301, compared to 216 at this time last year. The city's homicide record of 372 was set last year. Police say about 60 percent of the city's killings are related to drugs. Drug-related violence has also hiked the murder rate in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s suburbs, according to police. Twelve people have been killed so far this year in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, compared to nine at this time last year. In Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, 77 people have been killed this year, compared to 53 at this time in 1988. <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, has had 19 killings this year, compared to 12 last year, and <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, has eight compared to three last year.
