<HEAD>Last Rhode Island Beach Closed by June Oil Spill Reopening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> beach closed by an oil spill in June was prepared for reopening today as state crews plowed oil-soaked sand. Mackerel Cove in <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION> had been closed since the June 23 accident involving the Greek tanker World Prodigy. The tanker spilled about 300,000 gallons of home heating oil into <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> when it ran aground at <LOCATION> Brenton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>, about a mile south of <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> and five miles from Mackerel Cove. The spill caused most <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> beaches to be closed about a week, but Mackerel Cove, the hardest-hit of the beaches, remained closed because oil had soaked into the sand. State environmental workers have been harrowing the sand to expose the oil to air so it can evaporate. The department decided to bulldoze the rest of the contaminated sand instead of turning it because it is now a manageable amount, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Segerson </PERSON>.
