nto a contract with One <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` Since there's no contract, we do n't need a reason to kill it,'' said the source. The One America project had been put on hold by new <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>. Attempts to reach One <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> officials late Tuesday were unsuccessful. The telephone at the company was not answered. The company is owned by <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. During the early 1980s, Mrs. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> headed a group of black Republicans known as the Council of 100 and also served on a White House commission on small business. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> is a former <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official and was the first black to serve on the National Labor Relations Board. Mrs. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in July, said she had not received any special treatment from the agency. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> has not returned calls seeking comment. In a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said that getting more blacks involved in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> programs was one of his greatest achievements at the agency but said politics played no part in his decisions. `` A lot of blacks got business and we certainly did n't ask them were they Republicans, Democrat, liberal or what,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said.
