<HEAD>Tourist Group Votes to Put Off Admitting Palestine as Member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The World Tourism Organization voted to put off consideration of a membership application by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s self-declared state of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> until the organization meets again in 1991. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, supported by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, forced the vote Tuesday to delay the membership consideration afer daylong discussions. The vote was by secret ballot. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort was led by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for international organizations, who said he was `` very gratified'' by the outcome. The vote was 40-34 to postpone the issue, with six absentees, six abstentions and five blank votes. One diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was the first time he could recall a Soviet bloc country supporting a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> resolution at an international meeting. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains that bids by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to join international bodies threatens <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace efforts. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Massalha </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s observer mission to the Paris-based <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION>, Scientific and Cultural Organization, called the vote `` a bad decision.'' <PERSON> Massalha </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> would continue its efforts to join international organizations. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a sort of parliament-in-exile, proclaimed the state of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> last November. <LOC