<HEAD>Ros-Lehtinen First Cuban-American Elected To Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 26 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from winner, loser,
Republican and Democratic chairmans, editing to conform; picks up 20th
graf, `Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a ...' Should stand for AMs. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
pronounced ill-ee-AHN-ah ross-LAYT-ih-nen.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Havana-born Republican state senator rode heavy support from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s Hispanic community Tuesday to become the first Cuban-American elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, winning the seat held by the late <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> for nearly three decades. With all precincts reporting in the ethnically divisive race, state Sen. <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, 37, received 49,638 votes, or 53 percent, to 43,759, or 47 percent, for Brooklyn-born attorney <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>. The 48-year-old Democrat, who is Jewish, had been making his first run for elective office. The race was made necessary by Pepper's death May 30 at 88. Pepper, a Democrat, had held the seat since its inception 27 years ago The 93,000-plus turnout was nearly 51 percent, far higher than normal for a special election and higher than election officials' 43 percent projection. The outcome was delayed more than an hour late Tuesday by a <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> elections computer problem that temporarily halted vote-counting. Higher final counts for both candidates were revised early Wednesday because of the counting problems. The unofficial returns indicated that predominantly Hispanic precincts, with turnouts of more than 60 percent, boosted Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> with 80 to 90 percent margins, while <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> was favored by margins of 80 to 90 percent in predominantly black or non-Latin white precincts. In her victory speech, Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> said she wanted to unify and heal the community and `` provide leadership ... which is based on acaring conscience and conservative convictions. `` We do not have the luxury to waste time on divisive politics,'' she told cheering supporters at the Airport Hilton Hotel. `` We must focus on what we have in common and not ponder on the negative.'' <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>, addressing disappointed supporters at the Clarion Castle Hotel in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, said, `` We have done incredibly well and we did it on a positive theme.'' He said Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> outspent him and had campaign help from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>. The Democrat, noting that more Hispanics turned out than blacks or non-Hispanic whites, said, `` We've got to get everyone in this community to get out and exercise their right to vote. If that had happened, we would have won tonight.'' The Democrats, mindful that August is vacation month for many <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> residents, had tried to build an absentee-vote margin for <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>. But election officials said <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> had only 3,933 absentee votes to 3,599 for Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>. The victory gave the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> an 11-8 majority in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s congressional delegation, and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> called it a Republican milestone in the South `` That seat has been a Democratic seat since it was created,'' he said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` For us to win it is a major victory.'' Democratic Chairman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who campaigned for <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>, expressed disappointment in a statement issued by his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office, but said, `` The Democrats ran a surprisingly competitive race after an admittedly divisive primary.'' Ethnic-bloc campaigning dominated the short, tense race between Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> for the remaining 14 months of Pepper's term <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> had come under fire for declaring, `` This is an American seat.'' <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> had hoped to capitalize on the 30,000-plus edge that Democrats, mostly blacks, Jews and retirees, hold in registration. Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> looked to the Hispanic community, which makes up 40 percent-plus of the vote. Polls in the final week of the race had indicated it was too close to call. ` It's been a very controversial election,'' said <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Elections Supervisor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>. `` There has been a tremendous amount of media exposure, and we think both camps are getting a lot more people out to vote.'' Pepper's seat was one of five openings in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> House. The others were caused by the resignations of <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and the deaths of <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, R-Miss., in plane Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> had refused to appear with <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> during the campaign, charging his `` American seat'' message was bigoted. However, the same charges were made against her campaign over a Spanish-language mailing that urged Hispanics to show how American they were even though they were n't born in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and did n't speak English like <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>'s said his `` American seat'' remark was an appeal to voters to decide on qualifications, not birthplace. He also said it was a response to <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s statement that the party wanted to elect a Cuban-American. But many saw <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>'s theme as anti-Hispanic code. Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, a legislator for seven years, emphasized experience and populist appeal in her campaign. Her campaign chairman was the president's son <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, whose husband, <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, portrayed herself as tough on crime and drugs. But <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> argued that her legislative record against gun control showed softness on crime, because it allowed criminals easy access to guns. <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> also tried to make abortion an issue; he's pro-choice, Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> is for further restrictions on abortion. With polls indicating most voters were pro-choice, Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> claimed it was n't an issue. <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> president, stunned the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> establishment by breaking out of a seven-candidate pack to win narrowly the party's Aug. 1 primary, then trouncing erstwhile front-runner <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in an Aug. 15 runoff. Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> won the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination in the Aug. 1 primary. The district covers black neighborhoods such as <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, most of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> and sections of blue-collar <PERSON> Hispanic </PERSON> <PERSON> Hialeah </PERSON> and upscale Coral Gables and Key Biscayne.
