<HEAD>Environmentalists Say Banned Pesticides Enter U.S. in Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An environmental group says new laws are needed to prevent chemical companies from manufacturing highly toxic pesticides banned in this country and sending them abroad. The practice `` has created a circle of poison'' where some food tainted by the toxic chemicals is imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquardt </PERSON>, who has followed the issue for the environmental group <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> cited the practices of the <ORGANIZATION> Velsicol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which from its plant in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, is the world's only producer of the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor. Both pesticides are banned for agricultural use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and for virtually all other uses because they were found to cause cancer. They are also banned or severely restricted in 48 countries. Nevertheless, Ms. <PERSON> Marquardt </PERSON> said Tuesday, <PERSON> Velsicol </PERSON> exported nearly 5 million pounds of the pesticides to 25 countries between 1987 and the middle of this year. More than 330,000 pounds went to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and another 510,000 pounds to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, countries that import meat and other products into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In a statement from company headquarters in <LOCATION> Rosemont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Velsicol </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> report `` grossly inaccurate.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Appeals Court OKs Random Drug Tests for Some Army Civilians</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court says the Army may subject more than 6,500 civilian workers, including law enforcement and aviation personnel, to random drug tests. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 implemented drug testing for more than 9,000 of its 450,000 civilian employees. In a 3-0 decision Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> said 3,700 civilian police and guards should face mandatory drug tests because of the threat to public safety posed by `` drug-impaired, gun-toting civilian officers.'' The 2,800 civilians who fly and service the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s airplanes and helicopters also should undergo random drug testing due to the possibly `` calamitous consequences'' of a single drug-related lapse, the appeals court said. A small group of civilian lab workers do n't have to undergo mandatory, random testing, said <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON>.
