<HEAD>Voters in Four Counties Vote for Riverboat Gambling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters in four eastern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> counties approved riverboat gambling that would allow floating casinos to dock in their areas. In <LOCATION> Scott </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the largest of the four counties voting on the riverboat gambling initiative, the measure was approved by 23,999 votes, or nearly 60 percent, to 16,102, or 40 percent. `` A victory means this community has basically said ` come on in,''' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>, coordinator of Citizens for Riverboat Gambling in <LOCATION> Scott </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` It sends a message to developers and the Racing and <ORGANIZATION> Gaming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that we will support riverboat gambling if the commission wants it to come here,'' she said. `` I think it's an exciting concept.'' But the Rev. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> VanderJagt </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Newcomb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, was n't happy with the result. `` We're disappointed, surely,'' he said. `` We certainly are n't going to be poor sports about it `` This was an economic, moral and social issue. They are intertwined, whether you are talking about theft, compulsive gambling or prostitution. It sends the wrong signal.'' In <LOCATION> Muscatine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, voters gave the measure 3,939 votes, or 54 percent, to 3,315, or 46 percent. The proposal enjoyed wide support in <LOCATION> Clinton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, with 7,903 `` yes'' votes and 4,929 `` no'' votes for a margin of victory of 62 percent to 38 percent. The spread was much closer in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>: 1,598 votes for to 1,496 votes against. Under a 1989 law, floating casinos may begin operation on <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> waterways aboard excursion boats April 1, 1991, but only in counties where voters have given approval. Two weeks ago the riverboat gambling initiative was rejected in the northeast counties of <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> and Allamakee while it passed in <LOCATION> Dubuque </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Last Tuesday, voters in <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> counties in southeast <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> approved a gambling proposal. Along the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Woodbury </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> supervisors have set a Sept. 26 referendum while petitions were being circulated in <LOCATION> Mills </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The Legislature this year voted to authorize riverboat gambling, limiting betting to $ 5 per play and setting a $ 200 nightly limit on losses. Boats can offer blackjack, roulette, slot machines, dice games and video gambling. Passage of the issue is only a first step in the process. The <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gaming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will decide how many licenses to grant and where the boats will dock. Those decisions are not expected until next year.
