<HEAD>Menem Willing to Meet Thatcher to Discuss Falklands Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Argentine President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> was quoted in an interview today as saying he wants to meet with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in an attempt to resolve the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> dispute that led to a 74-day war in 1982. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> suggested such a meeting could take place during next month's session of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, in office since July, said he would welcome direct talks with Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> `` in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> or in any part of the world,'' <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> also said in the interview that he ruled out the possibility of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> forcefully trying to recover the Falklands, which it calls the <LOCATION> Malvinas </LOCATION> and has claimed since 1833. Their brief but bloody <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> war cost the lives of nearly 1,000 British and Argentine soldiers. `` This is completely ruled out, at least during my government. ... We will not use weapons to recover what we believe and are convinced is ours,'' <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> was quoted as saying. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> added that he would invite Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to the Argentine capital of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> if diplomatic relations between the two countries, which have been severed since the war, were restored, the paper reported. `` I am planning to do so if Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> is willing to talk to me,'' it quoted him as saying. The exclusive interview was by Times correspondent <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Llanos </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> but the paper did not say when it was conducted. There was no immediate reaction from Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government. But the British domestic news agency <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported without attribution: `` The view in <ORGANIZATION> Whitehall </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- British government circles -RRB- is that if President <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s words and proposals are accurately represented, this is an attitude which <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> welcomes. `` However, while his words will be studied closely in -LRB- Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s -RRB- Downing Street -LRB- office -RRB-, the feeling is that any British-Argentine dialogue should move forward one step at a time.'' Representatives of the two governments agreed during three days of talks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this month to hold a meeting of officials Oct. 17-18 in the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> to discuss proposed normalization of relations between the two nations. Similar talks in <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, in July 1984 broke off over the issue of sovereignty, with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> refusing to discuss sovereignty of the islands and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> insisting it stay on the agenda. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government has consistently refused to discuss sovereignty. But <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has dropped the insistence of the previous Argentine government headed by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s sovereignty claim must be the first issue considered in normalization talks. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> invaded the Falklands 325 miles off its southeast coast in April 1982 but <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> sent a task force and recaptured them in a war that eventually led the Argentine junta, which had ruled harshly for nearly eight years, to relinquish power upon the election of <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> claims the windswept islands as an inheritance from the days of Spanish colonial rule and says the British, who have ruled them as a colony since 1833, stole the islands. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has never formally declared an end to hostilities with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> since the 1982 war. Asked in the interview in The Times if he thought island sovereignty would be negotiated at any stage during his six-year term, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> was quoted as saying: `` It might, but it might not. We have waited 156 years -LRB- to recover the islands -RRB-. We can certainly wait a bit longer.'' Nearly 2,000 staunchly pro-British <ORGANIZATION> Falkland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> are fiercely opposed to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> ever gaining sovereignty. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> was quoted in the interview as saying that if full diplomatic relations between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> were restored, his government would allow airline flights and shipping services between <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and the Falklands. He was quoted as saying that this included the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> I, the Falklands' own merchant vessel that caused a stir in recent months by docking in neighboring ports in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.
