<HEAD>Spooked Bird Flees Authorities in Fast Footrace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCITUATE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A flightless bird the size of a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> marathoner gave authorities a good run and kicked an animal control officer before police surrounded him and ended his two-hour escapade. The bird, a relative of the ostrich, fled in terror Tuesday after he was accidentally freed from his owner's back yard. The owner's sons and police chased the emu, named PeeWee, through streets in this seaside town southeast of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> until police finally surrounded him with a wire fence in a pasture. PeeWee was taken to <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterinary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grafton </LOCATION> and given three stitches for a cut in the neck. The bird was expected to go home today. Emus are flightless Australian birds with long legs and huge three-toed feet. Owner <PERSON> Myrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Borysenko </PERSON> estimated PeeWee to be more than 6 feet tall. <PERSON> Borysenko </PERSON> said he got the bird as a chick three years ago. He said PeeWee was friendly but not very smart. `` Once he's outside the back yard, he has no point of reference. If I'm in the yard he will recognize me. But if he's outside the yard, he gets spooked,'' said <PERSON> Borysenko </PERSON>, who is a doctor of immunology and anatomy. He said a neighborhood child probably opened the backyard gate, letting PeeWee loose. <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Borysenko </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Justin </PERSON>, went to the front yard to collect the bird, but PeeWee became terrified and took off. `` As my son likes to say, as soon as he got out, his turbo kicked in and he was flying down the street,'' <PERSON> Broysenko </PERSON> said. At the town common, animal control officer <PERSON> Lesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> got a noose around PeeWee, but he leapt away and kicked her in the leg. `` His kick was about as hard as my horse could do, but I was n't hurt,'' she said After police surrounded him, animal rescuers took the bird to the medical center in a van. But <PERSON> Borysenko </PERSON> said his troubles are n't over. `` Now all I have to do is figure out how to get him home,'' he said. `` I guess I'll have to get a van.''
