<HEAD>EPA Review Condemns Proposed $500 Million Water Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of the proposed $ 500 million Two Forks dam reacted with anger after a five-month federal review condemned the water project as unnecessary and environmentally damaging. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> deputy regional administrator from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> who conducted the review, announced Tuesday that he was recommending the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> press on with efforts to kill the project. <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the decision was `` a classical example of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> bureaucratic arrogance that shows a full disregard for the competency and expertise of a host of federal, state and local agencies'' that supported the plan. `` You simply ca n't leave us high and dry,'' Mayor <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday in reaction to DeHihns' announcement. `` We have not been given a fair, objective appraisal of this project.'' The 615-foot-high dam to be built 25 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> near the confluence of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and its <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> would flood 30 miles of scenic river valley and canyon and the town of <LOCATION> Deckers </LOCATION>, which has fewer than 100 residents. `` The Two Forks dam and reservoir project would result in the loss of a major aquatic resource which provides irreplaceable stream fishery habitat and recreational resources near the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> metropolitan area,'' <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berle </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGA