examined.'' Besides flooding a prized trout stream, Two Forks would eliminate about 300 acres of wetlands, and it would alter the river channel with possible effects on threatened and endangered species downstream, including in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, where officials have been strongly opposed to the project. `` I caution that there are still powerful forces aligned against us,'' Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., said in a statement Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., called the decision a major setback `` This decision was made by unelected officials applying subjective standards to a project Coloradans have studied, decided upon, and funded,'' he said.
