<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-DeGreiff     08-30 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-De Greiff,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Woman Threatened by Drug Lords</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Justice Minister <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON>, who drug traffickers want dead, summed up the dangers of her job after taking office six weeks ago: `` If they want to kill you, they will _ with or without escort.'' At the time it was merely a realistic statement by a woman who at 32 holds one of the most dangerous government posts in the world. Then she became a target in an anonymous phone call from a man who said: `` You will be the next.'' Since 1984, her ministry has been a post few covet. In that year, drug traffickers murdered Justice Minister <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>. Then, a former justice minister, <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Parejo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, was wounded in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, where the government had sent him as ambassador because traffickers had threatened his life. Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> was threatened Thursday, according to press reports, and hours later she boarded a plane for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ three days before her original schedule _ amid rumors she had resigned. The reasons for her rush to confer with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials may help Mrs. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> meet one of her goals as a minister: to obtain money to pay for protection for <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> judges threatened by drug barons. The traffickers have vowed to kill 10 judges for every drug lord extradited to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. As justice minister, Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> is a member of a committee deciding on extraditions. `` People should not be afraid of carrying out their duties,'' she said in a Colombian radio interview three weeks ago. She told reporters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> earlier this week that she did not intend to quit and that she was asking the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration for $ 19 million to build a security system to protect judges and high officials in her ministry. The administration approved $ 65 million in emergency aid earlier this month for <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s war on drugs. Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> has made it clear that being a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister is the high point for her career as a lawyer. `` I got this job because I have experience,'' she said recently. She graduated in 1980 from the exclusive <ORGANIZATION> Bogota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rosary </ORGANIZATION>, a Roman Catholic institution. After working for a few months with her father, also a lawyer, she worked for other private firms developing administrative experience. Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> entered government service in 1986, when <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> became president. Her career began at the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. She later was appointed general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. She became justice minister on July 16 and took an immediate dislike to the tight security surrounding her and her husband, <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Paley </PERSON>, an Argentine public relations consultant, and their 3-year-old son. `` With all those armed guys protecting you, one must avoid going out. But that is part of the price being in the post,'' she said. `` I love my family, but I have less and less time with them,'' she added. `` I hope this situation will improve soon.'' It did not and when death squads killed leading presidential hopeful <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON> Aug. 18, Mrs. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiff </PERSON> became involved in an all-out government offensive against drug traffickers. As the government conducted raids across the nation, arresting suspected drug dealers and confiscating millions of dollars in property, said: `` I am not prepared for times of war like these.'' The statement was considered untimely, and rumors that she planned to resign became common in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. She said Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>: `` The threats are out there, but I am satisfied with my protection right now. I am determined that the integrity of our justice system survives this crisis and I hope to play my full part in assuring this.''
</TEXT>
