<FIRST>u i PM-Burma     08-30 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Deaths in Uprising Not `Worth Mentioning:' Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 So few students were killed during last year's pro-democracy uprising in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> that they were n't `` worth mentioning,'' the country's health and education minister said. Dr. <PERSON> Pe </PERSON> <PERSON> Thein </PERSON>, addressing a <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> meeting Tuesday of scholars just back from education overseas, said `` students must see the truth behind last year's incidents.'' A transcript of his remarks, reported in an official Radio <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> broadcast, was seen today in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. Diplomats, dissidents and international human rights groups estimate several thousand people were killed last year in a series of army clampdowns on student-led unrest from March to September. According to witness accounts and independent reports, scores of students were among those killed as troops fired indiscriminately into crowds of peaceful demonstrators. `` I do n't mean to say that there were no casualties, only that there were few casualties, of which students constitute so small a number as to be not worth mentioning,'' <PERSON> Pe </PERSON> <PERSON> Thein </PERSON> said. The military government admitted killing hundreds as it crushed dissent in September, but it said most were `` looters'' or `` destructive ... unscrupulous elements.'' Last June, all schools and universities throughout the country were closed because of the unrest. Though primary and middle schools recently re-opened, university and high schools remain closed. The minister said the country needed technocrats and intellectuals to reconstruct the nation, but `` school teachers -LRB- must -RRB- guide their students to becoming clever people and ... -LRB- to -RRB- avoid taking part in destructive acts.'' <PERSON> Pe </PERSON> <PERSON> Thein </PERSON> told the scholars that attempts were being made to try to divide the army and the people in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. He accused foreign broadcasting stations of using `` human rights issues to portray themselves as the only ones who love the country and report that the defense forces do not love the nation.'' `` The defense forces have been portrayed by some as a barbaric force,'' he said. He warned teachers, as public servants, to stay clear of party politics. `` Despite repeated warnings, we have had to part ways with some -LRB- teachers -RRB- because of their contacts with political parties,'' he said. Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> have reported authorities arrested at least 2,000 people since putting the two leaders of the main opposition group under house arrest on July 20. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and Tin Oo, who head the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, were accused of trying to divide the people and the military after criticizing the government's human rights record. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> says it has received `` credible'' reports that many pro-democracy activists have been tortured, sometimes fatally, after being arrested.
