<HEAD>Probe of L.A. Mayor Reportedly Uncovers No Criminal Impropriety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City investigators who have spent nearly five months scrutinizing the personal finances of Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> have uncovered no evidence of criminal wrongdoing, it was reported today. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> could be fined for alleged improper financial disclosures, but the man recently re-elected to an unprecedented fifth term is unlikely to face any criminal charges, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> reported. A final report from City Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> is expected sometime in September. `` The process still is going on. Anything can happen in two weeks,'' the Times quoted an unnamed source as saying. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> has said he would not comment on the investigation until the report is released. <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>'s inquiry focuses on the 71-year-old mayor's connection to <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which paid <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> $ 18,000 as a consultant. After some inquiries by <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, City Treasurer <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> subsequently had $ 2 million in city funds deposited with the bank. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said he did not pressure <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> says he has not been pressured. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> later returned the $ 18,000 fee. The city attorney also is looking into whether <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> violated conflict-of-interest laws by accepting payments from <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, as well as more than 100 errors in the mayor's disclosures regarding extensive stock portfolio and property holdings. <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> plans to recommend that the city fine <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> about $ 200,000 for his financial reporting violations, the newspapers reported. In addition to the local probe, federal investigators are probing <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s many investments with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the former junk-bond king who recently resigned after being indicted for fraud.
