of any professional athlete for steriod use. A longer version moved on
sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE GOLDBERG ^AP Football Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> suspended 13 players who tested positive for steroids, indicating that warnings of a crackdown on the muscle-building drugs months ago may have worked. The action marked the first time <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> professional athletes had been suspended for steriod use. No other league conducts mandatory tests for the drugs. The small number of suspensions under the new steroid policy seemed to please even the <ORGANIZATION> NFL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Players </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which has challenged the accuracy of tests and the suspensions. `` The fact that so few players have been suspended for alleged steroid use indicates that the public perception of the steroid problem in the <ORGANIZATION> NFL </ORGANIZATION> is greatly exaggerated,'' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Upshaw </PERSON>, executive director of the union and former All-Pro guard. Of the 13 players suspended for four weeks, only Pro Bowl guard <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Solt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagles </ORGANIZATION> was of any prominence. Meanwhile, two other prominent players were suspended for using illegal drugs. All-Pro cornerback <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Irvin </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Rams and tight end <PERSON> Orson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mobley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> will miss the final exhibition game and the first three regular-season games. Commissioner <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozelle </PERSON> announced the steroid policy on March 21, saying he wanted to allow time for players who might be using steroids to get them out of their system before the start of training camp. A letter detailing the plan was sent 10 days later to all players. In both 1987 and 1988, 6 percent of