<HEAD>Primate's Comments on Jews Stir New Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to MOVE UP Polish newspaper criticism, and
edits to conform. Pickup 11th pvs, `Referring to...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Roman Catholic journalist, in a rare criticism of the church, said Cardinal <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s remarks about Jews may be `` deeply wounding'' to people who lost loved ones in the Nazi holocaust. Criticism of <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comments on Jewish-Catholic relations spread worldwide on Tuesday, although some <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> clerics said the Polish primate's remarks may have been misconstrued. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> told pilgrims at <ORGANIZATION> Jasna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gora </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monastery </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION> on Saturday that Polish anti-Semitism would disappear if Jews abandon `` anti-Polonism,'' or anti-Polish sentiments. He asked Jews to understand that it offended Poles' religious sensibilities and feelings of sovereignty to insist on removal of a Carmelite convent set up on the edge of the former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. `` Dear Jews, do not talk to us from the position of a nation elevated over all others and do not put to us conditions that are impossible to meet,'' <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> said. But he intensified charges of anti-Semitism by using language that invoked the image of Jews spreading communism and by saying that <PERSON> Jews </PERSON> collaborated with <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II, that Jews as businessmen neglected or detested Poles and that Jews have easy access to mass media. Polish <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> journalist <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON> said: `` The expressions used by the primate, even contrary to his intentions, pose a danger of deeply wounding the feelings of many of those who are descendants and brothers of the Holocaust victims.'' The rare published criticism appeared Monday in the Polish opposition's <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. Cardinal <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCourtray </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, said Tuesday it was unlikely that <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s words were meant the way they were received. He said the `` primate and bishops of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> can not be accused of an anti-Semitism, which they denounce.'' Referring to <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comment about easy Jewish access to mass media, the International League against <ORGANIZATION> Racism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Semitism </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that he had `` made use of arguments used against Jews by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> yesterday and by the extreme right in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> today.'' <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON>, a legislator from the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said Tuesday in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, `` Anti-Semitism has a long history in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and I think it is ridiculous to talk about ` anti-Polonism.''' <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi, <PERSON> Elio </PERSON> <PERSON> Toaff </PERSON>, said in a newspaper interview that the question of anti-Semitism is something the church `` has to face. ... The analysis has to be deep enough to eradicate once and for all the anti-Semitism that still exists in many countries, like <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' `` It is particularly serious that it was <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, one noted for diplomacy and political gifts, who confused cause and effects,'' said <PERSON> Tullia </PERSON> <PERSON> Zevi </PERSON>, head of the Union of Italian Jewish Communities, quoted in the same article Monday in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s I Messaggero. The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> issued a statement Monday calling <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comments `` malicious and out of place.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardinal </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said Tuesday he was `` shocked'' by <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s `` harmful'' remarks. In a news conference, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> also called on Polish church officials to honor their commitment to move the Carmelite convent at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. The convent site has been criticized as offensive because an estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of <LOCATION> Auschwitz-Birkenau </LOCATION> were executed simply for being Jewish. Only several thousand Jews live in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> today compared with a pre-war Jewish population of 3.5 million. Relations between the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and Jewish groups have been strained since Aug. 10 when Cardinal <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Macharski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, whose diocese includes the camp, announced the church was suspending a 1987 agreement to move the convent. He said it could not fulfill the agreement in an atmosphere of `` aggressive demands.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comments could be construed to shift `` the blame to the Jews for demanding that a signed accord be carried out.'' `` I do n't think that is just, and I do n't think that is charitable. And it certainly does n't represent my position,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. The proposal to remove the convent, founded in 1984 just outside the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> fence, has found little sympathy in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Poles have argued that thousands of the victims at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> were Polish political prisoners, including many priests and nuns. Most Poles acknowledge that anti-Semitism still exists in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. But some say its depth is exaggerated and note that many Poles risked their lives to protect Jews during the war.
