<HEAD>Moldavians Considering Language Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, in an effort to placate outraged minority groups, proposed today that the republic adopt a weaker version of a law making Moldavian the official language, an activist said. The compromise, which reportedly resulted from a telephone conversation between the party chief and President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, is aimed at stopping widespread strikes and other protests in the republic. The initial proposed law would substitute Moldavian for Russian in virtually all government and business transactions in the republic. Russians and other minorities in the republic say the proposal is discriminatory. The proposed compromise, outlined to the Supreme Soviet by <LOCATION> Moldavian </LOCATION> party chief <PERSON> Semen </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossu </PERSON>, would make Moldavian the language for government officials and documents, and Russian the tongue for everyday contact among the republic's ethnic groups. The compromise was reported by <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Nestase </PERSON>, a leader of the pro-Moldavian People's Front who spoke by telephone from the republic's capital, <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, now has no law specifying which language is to be used, but Russian has traditionally been the tongue for government affairs. <PERSON> Grossu </PERSON> proposed the compromise after reporting he had spoken with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> by telephone Tuesday night about the language controversy. The Moldavian party chief did not say whether <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had suggested the compromise, but <PERSON> Nestase </PERSON> said it was widely believed this was the case. `` We think this is the most realistic compromise,'' <PERSON> Nataly </PERSON> <PERSON> Pascal </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> member, said in a telephone interview. `` We support this compromise and we're not the only ones.'' The Moldavian Supreme Soviet began debating the proposal on Tuesday, and <PERSON> Nestase </PERSON> said the session would continue Thursday. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has quietly been involved in several attempts recently to quell nationalist unrest breaking out in may of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s republics. He told the Lithuanian party chief during the weekend that the independence movement there had gone too far. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also `` worked out'' with other members of the ruling Politburo a tough party statement Saturday condemning nationalism, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> told a news briefing Tuesday. The statement by the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> warned that independence movements were leading the country into an `` abyss.'' A strike organizer in the Moldavian city of <LOCATION> Tiraspol </LOCATION>, where Russians and other minorities walked off their jobs last week to protest the proposed language law, said strikers were willing to consider the compromise even though they would still prefer that Russian and Moldavian be given equal status. The weekly <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News today highlighted unemployment as a factor in the republic's unrest. It said at least 150,000 of the republic's 4.2 million people are unemployed, and the number is growing Pravda repeated earlier criticism of <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> activists, accusing them of `` spreading the seeds of separatism and nationalism'' and claiming that Moldavian parliamentarians ordered Pravda correspondent to leave the republic. The Supreme Soviet session addressing the law opened Tuesday, and several thousand people, some carrying red-yellow-and-blue Moldavian banners, gathered after the debate in downtown <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION> to show support for the People's Front. `` We have to seize the moment,'' said <PERSON> Ala </PERSON> <PERSON> Myndycanu </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> governing council. `` We have to solve our problems before <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> does.'' But non-Moldavian activists, members of the Russian-language group <PERSON> Yedinstvo </PERSON>, warned that `` life wo n't be quiet'' if the original law was passed over the objections of strikers. Disgruntled Russian-speaking residents of the republic are striking at almost 200 factories and offices to protest the bill, said <PERSON> Vsevolod </PERSON> <PERSON> Yampolsky </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Tiraspol </LOCATION> strike committee. Most of the strikes are in cities with large <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> populations. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported today that railroad workers in several <LOCATION> Moldavian </LOCATION> cities had joined the strike. The portion of the bill that would be cut out under the compromise would have made Moldavian the language among Russians, Ukrainians, Jews, Bulgarians, and other nationalities in the republic. That goes farther than the language laws in a number of other republics. Many non-Moldavians do not speak Moldavian, but they share some knowledge of Russian as a result of Soviet schooling. The law also would restore the Latin alphabet, replacing the Cyrillic imposed by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> after he annexed <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> in 1940. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> imposed the Cyrillic, used in Russian, to back up his claim that Romanians and Moldavians are two distinct nationalities. Ethnic Moldavians make up 64 percent of the republic's 4.2 million people.
