<HEAD>Solidarity Lawmaker: Break Communist Monopoly on Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Solidarity lawmaker criticized the Communists' foreign policy record today and suggested a non-Communist official should be named foreign minister in Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>'s new government. <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>, head of the Solidarity parliamentary delegation, also said in the pro-Solidarity <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> newspaper today that the Communists should assume at least one economic ministry so the party would have a sense of `` co-responsibility'' for economic policy. Communist leaders have been pressing to keep the ministry of foreign affairs in the hands of current Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON>, a party member. The post is one of several areas of conflict as <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, a longtime Solidarity activist, forms the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first government led by non-Communists. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> has said that the new government would be announced before Sept. 10. <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> assumed office on Aug. 24. `` Experiences in Polish foreign policy ... indicate that the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- does not serve'' national interests, <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said in the interview published today. He cited a recent agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> ally <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> over disputed waters in the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> near the port of <LOCATION> Szczecin </LOCATION>, which many Poles believe was settled to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s disadvantage. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> noted that the information department of the foreign ministry legally `` functions as a service unit for the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'' of the party. This `` does not correspond to the requirements of the new period,'' he said. Although <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> did not say specifically that the ministry should be taken away from the party, his remarks about breaking the party's monopoly on foreign policy appeared to indicate that the ministry should go either to Solidarity or one of two minor allied parties, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peasants </LOCATION> and the Democrats. <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who is acting as the party's envoy in the coalition talks with <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, argued strongly Tuesday for the party to retain control of the ministry. `` We think that the best candidate is <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON>,'' he said in an interview with the party paper <PERSON> Trybuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludu </PERSON>. `` If professionalism is a criterion, then undoubtedly <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON> is an expert of the highest class.'' He also cited <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s alliances in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc that he said have protected national security. `` No matter what you accuse the party of, its foreign policy is not subject to criticism,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` It has guaranteed us a safe, stable place in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s favorable position in the world and alliances which allow us a feeling of national security. `` Society needs this feeling and it has to be maintained.'' <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said he favored only limited participation by the Communists in the <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> government. `` Broad participation.. would not be understandable to public opinion,'' he said. Solidarity already has promised the Communists control of the important defense and interior ministries, which control the army and police. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> reiterated in today's article that the party ought to take one of the five economic ministries: finance, agriculture, foreign trade, labor or industry. That way it `` could not be in opposition to the government's economic policy and spread social demagogy,'' he said. He suggested that non-Communist adminstrators serve just below the defense and interior ministers. Another controversial area is control of the mass media. <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said the committee that oversees state radio and television should be put under control of parliament, where Solidarity and its allies hold a majority. Personnel decisions in radio and television will be one of the quickest signs of change under the new government, <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> said.
