<HEAD>Democrats Say Bush Isn't Filling Top Vacancies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs graf 8, A telephone call, with White House comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration appears to be largely `` on automatic pilot'' because of the president's failure to fill many top executive branch positions, Democratic congressional researchers say. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had not nominated anyone by Aug. 9 to fill 160 of the top 394 positions requiring <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` It is believed that this number of vacancies so late in a president's first year in office is without precedent,'' the report said. Among them, although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he wants to be remembered as an `` education president,'' are five of the seven assistant secretaries of education, it said. Four assistant administrator slots are vacant at the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the president has not nominated anyone as chairman of the Council on Environmental Quality, the report said. Openings were also listed for three undersecretaries and 13 assistant secretaries in other departments. `` It appears as though a significant portion of the government is on automatic pilot,'' said the DSG, an organization of House Democrats that provides research papers to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The DSG said it did not have comparable figures for past administrations, although its analysis in May showed that four previous presidents had made appointments during their first six weeks in office at a pace two to four times as fast as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Deputy White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, reached by telephone in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where the president is vacationing, said the administration's count is not the same as the DSG's. `` Their numbers conflict because they wanted to go with the broadest brush to try and add to the sensational nature of their conclusions,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. The White House counts 308 presidential appointments within the Cabinet departments. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said appointees to 129 of these posts have been confirmed, and 38 are awaiting confirmation. He said 25 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointees had been retained and 84 candidates were now being cleared for appointment. He said most of the remaining 37 vacancies had candidates under consideration. `` The notion that somehow <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been crippled by the fact that he has n't got all of his assistant secretaries in place just does n't make any sense,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. The DSG report dealt with a larger figure because it included posts outside of the Cabinet departments. The report said that as of Aug. 10, only 156 of the 394 positions were filled by an appointee confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Nominations for 60 positions were awaiting confirmation, and remain so since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been in recess. Two nominations, of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> to be secretary of defense and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> to be assistant attorney general for civil rights, were rejected. Tower was turned down by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. For 16 positions, appointees of former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> have been asked to remain on the job. `` It is not clear how the failure to fill so many key positions in a timely manner will affect the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration or the country generally,'' the report said. `` It does, however, appear to set the administration on a course that is virtually 180 degrees at variance with the prevailing view of scholars and former White House officials on how the presidency should be managed.'' Defenders of the administration have argued that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not need to move quickly because he succeeded a president of his own party and thus did not need to make major policy changes. The DSG, however, said the slower pace `` could be as important a liability to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration as it would be to any other.'' Even if the remaining nominations are made and confirmed quickly this fall, those people would have missed most of the planning for next year's budget and legislative initiatives, the report said. All of the Cabinet positions have been filled. However, posts for which no nomination has been made and no <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> holdover is in place include two assistant secretaries of agriculture, an undersecretary of commerce, a deputy undersecretary and six assistant secretaries of defense, an assistant secretary of energy, two assistant secretaries of health and human services, two assistant secretaries of housing and urban development, an assistant secretary of the interior, a deputy attorney general and associate attorney general, an undersecretary and an assistant secretary of state, an undersecretary and an assistant secretary of the treasury and three assistant secretaries of veterans' affairs. The only department at which all the top posts have been filled is Transportation, the report said.
