<HEAD>Minorities, Women Accept Out-of-Court Settlement on Discrimination
Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of minority and female police officers that sued the city for discrimination has accepted a settlement after recent <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings against affirmative action programs. `` There are mixed feelings,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Drew </PERSON>, the attorney representing the 10 minority and 11 female officers. `` Considering the latest rulings, we did not feel that the laws of this country, as interpreted by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, are favorable to minority and female litigants.'' According to the settlement, the city will pay the officers $ 325,000, including court costs and attorney fees. It was not disclosed how much each person would receive, <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> recently issued decisions to restrict affirmative action programs and make it more difficult for plaintiffs to prove discrimination in the workplace. In March 1988, the minority officers _ eight blacks, a Hispanic and an American Indian _ sued the city, seeking $ 4.6 million in damages. Two months later, 11 female officers filed a similar suit seeking more than $ 1.6 million. Both suits alleged the officers were denied promotional opportunities because of their race or gender. The two cases were joined for the purpose of settlement talks. The trial was to begin Sept. 12. At the time the suits were filed, only one of the department's 45 command officers _ sergeant and above _ was classified as a minority. At the heart of both suits was a written exam and performance evaluation for the position of sergeant that the officers said were discriminatory and never had been validated to ensure they conformed to civil rights regulations. The city has agreed to hire an independent consultant to develop a professionally validated test for sergeant promotions. <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> said the timing of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings made it impractical for him to take the case to court. He said he believes the settlement `` indicates a willingness on the city's part to put the bad behind us and move forward. Hopefully that will lead to better minority and female representation on the police force.''
