<FIRST>r w PM-SchoolLunch     08-30 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Lunch,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Fat-Laden Foods Barrier to Healthy School Lunches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Free `` fat-laden foods'' given to schools by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> are key obstacles to healthy school lunch programs, a consumer nutrition group said today. Sixty-seven percent of the school food service directors questioned this spring by <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s commodity distribution program is one of the most significant barriers to their efforts to provide nutritious meals. The school lunch programs depend upon commodities provided free of charge by the federal government to help them stay afloat financially, `` yet the commodities offered include a high proportion of fat-laden foods,'' said the report, which is a followup to previous studies assessing the progress being made to reduce fat in school lunches. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, acting administator of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the department is committed to dietary guidelines developed jointly with the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. But he said the guidelines do n't set quantitative standards for fat, and `` there is no scientific consensus on appropriate levels of fat in children's diets.'' More than 80 percent of the directors agreed that efforts are needed to reduce fat in their school lunches and said they have taken some steps toward that end. Yet many of the directors said they were unaware that most health authorities agree that fat in children's diets should be reduced to about 30 percent of calories, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> said. Twenty-eight percent were uncertain of the proper average level of fat in school lunches. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> has provided only limited guidance to the directors on how to cut back on fat to achieve this level, such as through comprehensive hands-on training in meal preparation or guidance on working with food suppliers,'' said the study. Other findings included: _ Only 6 percent of the directors have established target levels or ranges for fat in their programs Central city school districts are eight times more likely to establish such limits than are rural districts. _ Twenty-three percent of those questioned said they did not receive any guidance or guidelines on how to purchase foods or modify recipes to reduce fat The rest reported having limited access to written materials or training programs. _ When asked to identify the single most important thing that could be done to help reduce fat, 50 percent said change the commodity program and 26 percent said provide nutrition education Public Voice recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> provide greater leadership in educating school food service directors and in offering assistance in planning monthly menus, including suggesting how often specific foods should be served. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also should significantly expand the availability of lower-fat commodities to the schools, the group added. <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said `` it is important to remember that no matter what level is deemed appropriate, that level must be applied to a person's entire diet, not to a single food or a single meal <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> can not at this time support setting quantitative fat standards or recommended frequency of serving certain foods.'' The variety of foods donated to schools is under constant review, he said in a statement, adding that `` over the years significant progress has been made in providing more and more healthy, wholesome foods, including additional low-and reduced-fat foods.'' In addition, the agency promotes and coordinates nutrition education and technical assistance for all involved in the school lunch program, he said. But states `` have great flexibility in how they spend the money they have available for training.'' `` Technical assistance and educational materials have recently been revised and distributed to school food service directors,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said. `` These include recipe cards, a commodity foods newsletter and information on fat and cholesterol.''
</TEXT>
