<HEAD>Trains Collide; 1 Dead, 27 Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE casualties. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two passenger trains collided head-on in western <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> today, killing at least one person and injuring 27 people, a railway spokesman said. Three cars derailed when the trains crashed while traveling at relatively low speeds between <LOCATION> Bregenz </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Voralberg </LOCATION> province, and the small town of <LOCATION> Wolfurt </LOCATION>, the spokesman said. Authorities found one body in the wreckage. The <ORGANIZATION> Austria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> identified the victim as <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainer </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, a 48-year-old engineer from <LOCATION> Bodolz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Sixteen people, including the drivers of each train, were hospitalized and 11 other people treated for slight injuries, a railroad spokesman on condition of anonymity. The spokesman said 72 passengers were on the `` Montfort,'' the express train between <LOCATION> Bregenz </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>; and 75 were on the `` <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>,'' the express train between <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>. The railway spokesman said it seemed that human error was probably to blame since the `` Montfort'' had been erroneously switched to the same track as the other train. The crash occurred in <LOCATION> Voralberg </LOCATION> near the site of a train accident that killed five people and injured 46 exactly one year ago, on Aug. 29, 1988.
