<HEAD>Thieves Stealing Government Phone Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Widespread thievery has deprived Chinese officials of one of their most treasured privileges: access to telephones that work. The Worker's Daily said Wednesday that 420 miles of telephone line have been stolen this year in the southern island province of <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION>, and that lines or equipment have been damaged in 18 <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION> cities. It said thieves have preyed on the exclusive lines linking government offices. The lines are far clearer than the static-filled lines used by ordinary citizens. An important line from the southern <LOCATION> Hainan </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Sanya </LOCATION> to the provincial government in <LOCATION> Haikou </LOCATION> was cut for two months from February, and then cut again after it was repaired in April. The thieves, mostly peasants who sell the copper wire, made off with 37 -LCB- miles of a 49-mile stretch between <LOCATION> Sanya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tongshi </LOCATION> and 69 out of 87 -LCB- miles of line linking another two towns. When the provincial government tried to hold a telephone conference with <LOCATION> Tongshi </LOCATION> city on Aug. 17, it found the line was dead, the report said. Officials switched to a backup line that worked for only eight minutes before being cut by thieves.
