<TEXT>
 A 94-car freight train collided with a tractor-trailer rig today, killing two people, derailing at least 19 cars and snarling traffic for miles, police said. It was not immediately clear how many of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> freight train cars left the tracks; reports ranged from 19 to 30 cars. Many of the train's cars were empty and it was not known what the others held. Officials said they did not contain hazardous materials. Two bodies were pulled from the wreckage, both believed to have been in the truck, which was dragged about 50 yards on impact, said state Police Chief <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>. Their identities were not released. Three people aboard the train were reported injured, although none seriously. The train and truck, leased to <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frozen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, collided about 6:20 a.m. on a major city thoroughfare, said state police Lt. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Crain </PERSON>. The accident, near the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> University-Shreveport </LOCATION> campus, tied up traffic in the area for miles, officials said. Witnesses said freight cars were piled atop one other, scattered down a hillside and stuck on the ground. The <ORGANIZATION> Shreveport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> quoted eyewitnesses as saying the accident occurred when the truck drove past warning lights in front of the train.
