<TEXT>
 An artist boycott has forced the cancellation of two scheduled exhibitions at the Corcoran Gallery, which in June amid a swirling political controversy abruptly canceled a show that included sexually explicit photos. Gallery officials said Wednesday that contemporary artist <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemieux </PERSON> has withdrawn her one-woman show scheduled for Oct. 28 to Dec. 31 and that an exhibit by six sculptors scheduled for next Feb. 3 to April 8 also has been `` indefinitely postponed.'' `` We're hoping to reschedule both at some point,'' said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Shriver </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the private gallery, which has been trying in recent years to establish itself as a showcase for contemporary art. Ms. <PERSON> Lemieux </PERSON>, whose work was subsidized by the federal government through the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, described the withdrawal of her show as a `` indefinite postponement ... until they -LRB- the Corcoran -RRB- demonstrate a definite change in policy.'' Both she and two of the six sculptors said in letters to the gallery their decisions were based on the <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON>'s cancellation in June of an exhibit of 150 photographs by the late <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON>, who died last March from AIDS. `` We believe the <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON>, by its regrettable decision, not only compromised its own curatorial standards, but also demonstrated it complicity with the punishment subsequently attempted against other art instititions,'' wrote sculptors <PERSON> Buss </PERSON> <PERSON> Spector </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipski </PERSON>. The Mapplethrope exhibit _ which included photographs of children's genitalia, homoerotic and sadomasochistic images _ became embroiled in a vehement cont