<HEAD>Cambodia Peace Conference Fails</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with conference issuing final statement,
deciding to suspend its work. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates at an international conference on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> failed to produce a peace accord today and decided to suspend their work until the warring factions are ready to compromise. Last-minute haggling delayed by seven hours the issuing of a final statement that fell far short of the comprehensive settlement delegates from 19 nations hoped to achieve when the meeting opened in late July. The statement _ issued as the delegates began a last plenary session that was expected to be brief _ said the meeting had `` achieved progress in elaborating a wide variety of elements necessary for the reaching of a comprehensive settlement to the tragic conflict in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.'' But, it added, `` It is not yet possible to achieve a comprehensive settlement. It was therefore decided to suspend the conference.'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, whose representatives chaired the meeting, offered to assist in mediating within the next six months between the Vietnam-installed government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> and the three resistance factions led by Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, the hereditary ruler of the Southeast Asian nation. The delegates left open the possiblity of using the committees set up under the auspices of the international conference as a forum for future talks between the belligerents. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> `` will begin consultations within six months with the participants in the conference with a view to reconvening the conference,'' the statement said. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> called the conference when it appeared that an international political climate of greater cooperation favored a possible settlement. But over three weeks of negotiations in small working groups, the positions among the Cambodian factions hardened. The failure at the negotiating table in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> increased the liklihood of full-scale civil war after the scheduled withdrawal of 26,000 Vietnamese troops before Sept. 27, some delegates said. `` It will be like <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>; there will be more fighting,'' said the spokesman for the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> delegation, <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Koh </PERSON>. `` The two sides are preparing for war, they're already fighting.'' `` The parties wo n't come back until they've tested each other on the battlefield and have reached an impasse,'' <PERSON> Koh </PERSON> said. Negotiations broke down over five points, including the composition of a transitional government after the troop pullout, a mechanism for monitoring the withdrawal and the use of the word `` genocide'' in describing the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> rule between 1975 and the Vietnamese invasion three years later, French Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> is believed to have killed 1 million Cambodians during its rule. Intransigence marked the meeting up until the end, delaying the final plenary session that was scheduled to begin in the morning but was delayed until late afternoon. The points of disagreement included an item in a draft of the final statement calling for the Cambodian parties to intensify their `` efforts to achieve national reconciliation.'' Both <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, who supports the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> resistance, and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> objected to the reference national reconciliation, and the wording was deleted. Their position remains that the <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> government led by <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> is strictly a Vietnamese puppet. In a statement released on the last day of the conference, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said that the resistance would reject any international monitoring of the troop withdrawal `` before the dismantling of the illegal regime of <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> and its replacement by a Cambodian provisional quadrapartite government'' composed of the three resistance members and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>.
