<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised today to keep trying `` to hold the line on taxes'' and to fight for a lower tax on capital gains. Speaking to an appreciative audience of fellow residents and merchants of this summer resort, the vacationing president appealed for their support as he heads back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week to grapple with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over taxes and the deficit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> later in the day was welcoming Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and family to his oceanfront home, where he has spent the past two weeks. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, standing on a blue-draped temporary platform erected on a hotel shuffleboard court, with the rocky coastline and blue waters of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> at his back, noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Kennebunk-Kennebunkport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> was composed of `` a lot of entrepreneurs.'' `` I'd be remiss at a meeting like this if I did n't ask you to give me strong support as I go back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to fight for a capital gains tax differential,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to reduce the levy on capital gains _ profits made from the sale of property or securities _ from 28 percent to 15 percent but has met resistence from Democrats who control <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Calling small businesses `` the backbone of this country in any ways,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he wants to reduce the levy to stimulate the economy and reward `` those who have the courage to go off on their own and start new businesses.'' `` I do believe we're going to get a good agreement on the budget deficit reduction package. I think it will be accomplished without raising the taxes on the American working man,'' the president said. `` I am going to continue to try to hold the line on taxes,'' he told the crowd of several hundred. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made no apologies for his 20-day vacation, which ends on Labor Day. `` We are doing some work, but I have confessed at the very outset that this is a pure, total vacation, and I'm not going to look busy in order to convince people in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that it's something other than a vacation,'' he said to applause. `` It's the way it is.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also said he planned to call the editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> and ask him to stop running a graphic chronicling his futility at fishing. He said this morning he was at the helm when a companion caught a bluefish. `` I think they should knock off that advertisement on the front of the <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> paper that shows a bluefish with a big ` X' through it telling me that yet a 13th day I have n't caught one,'' he said. `` I'm going to appeal to them on that one.'' The president said this was a place where he and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> `` refurbish our souls and get our batteries all charged up and enjoy life really to the fullest.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has spent every summer of his life here except 1944, when he was flying <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> bombers in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> during World War II. A bright sun broke through the morning haze and clouds in time for the Chamber of Commerce event. `` I ca n't wait to show off this heaven to the prime minister of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, his wife and his four kids,'' he told the local boosters. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s national security adviser said Tuesday that U.S.-Canadian relations are in good shape thanks to progress on acid rain and trade as the two leaders hold their friendly, private visit. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, his wife <PERSON> Mila </PERSON> and their four children were to arrive in late afternoon at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s Point compound for an overnight visit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s national security adviser, <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, said Tuesday the private visit would give the two leaders `` a chance to relax -LRB- and -RRB- a chance to exchange views'' on world events, including the dramatic changes in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as well as the crises in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON> said the two old friends share `` a close similarity of views ... on world affairs and a kind of unique personal closeness and frankness in exchanging views.'' Scowcroft said U.S.-Canadian ties are `` in basically pretty good shape,'' with efforts under way to implement the sweeping Free Trade Agreement signed last year by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed revision of the Clean Air Act, which would seek to sharply curb emissions from utility plants, factories and other sources of pollutants that cause acid rain, `` has set us on the road to dealing with one of the other major problems between us, that is the issue of cross-border pollution'' such as acid rain.
