<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0829</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the country: Aug. 25 <LOCATION> Owatonna </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on education: <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> did not actually point an accusing finger at educators and schools when he complained of rising education costs and falling returns. He was careful to say parents, teachers and all Americans must become involved if education is to succeed. But his underlying tone was an accusatory one _ once again, he implied, education is falling down on the job. If <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> genuinely believes such a direct relationship can be discerned between money spent on education and children's achievement, he does not understand how people learn It is not the fault of the education system that families break apart and create insecure homes for kids, keeping their minds off learning. It is not the fault of the educational system that children are abused, throwing up barriers to learning. It is not the fault of the educational system that teen-agers get pregnant and, to compound the problem, try to raise their babies themselves, in poverty. A failure in education is a failure in society as a whole. We can not mend our school system until we mend our social failings. It is a cyclical relationship; to a large degree, education is the answer to our social failings. The circuit breaker we need is in the cycle of poverty and crime, not in the money we spend on education. Then again, it is possible that <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> realizes these complexities. If so, he is playing politics with children's futures and that is unforgivable.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 23 The News Tribune, <LOCATION> Woodbridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, on the cost of AZT: The encouraging news that the drug AZT will stall the deadly effect of the AIDS virus is dampened by the news that the bill for this drug might approach $ 5 billion annually. Should limited public funds be used to help these patients with their terminal virus, or should they be used to help poor women get proper prenatal care, or allow poor schoolchildren hot lunches? Providing AZT to all who need it, regardless of their ability to pay, is the compassionate thing to do. But is it fiscally responsible to do so in a nation with a mounting debt and an exploding health bill? What this dilemma does is offer an additional reminder that massive education, and changes in habits are needed to prevent the spread of this preventable disease. It also highlights the need for research to find a cure for AIDS as well as the need for discovery of affordable means of treatment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 27 Picayune -LRB- Miss. -RRB- Item on Voyager 2: Twelve long years and billions of miles after launching, the plucky Voyager spacecraft rendezvoused with the distant planet <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>, sending back a wealth of spectacular pictures and other information. It was a dramatic climax to a remarkable mission. This is technology at its best. Technology often gets a bum rap these days. People ask why we should spend so much on such adventures when there are so many problems here on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> tells us why. We want to know what's there, over the next hill. <LOCATION> Mankind </LOCATION> always has. Maybe what we find will be good or beneficial, maybe it wo n't. But we do n't know till we look, till we use our human resources to invent, to dream, to venture beyond our safe little backyards. The desolation of the other planets that <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> has so graphically shown us has been a lesson in itself. Our Earth is a special place, a unique oasis of beauty and knowledge in the vastness of space. We must preserve it, to be sure, but we must also make the most of what we have _ always thankful for our blessings, always willing to use them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 25 The Westerly -LRB- <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> -RRB- Sun on <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s drug crackdown: It is with a sense of deep satisfaction Americans watch the courageous move by the imperilled <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government as it rounded up close to 10,000 drug suspects in an all-out search for the five men who control the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel and their associates. ... This effort to stop the production and flow of cocaine and crack in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> comes too late for 550 provincial judges, the country's leading presidential candidate, and countless drug enforcement officers, senators, farmers, witnesses, bystanders, all killed by the cartel for getting in the way of the flow of coke from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to the streets of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> It comes too late for the thousands killed in this country each month in crack-related violence. But <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> is finally doing something. It is doing more than its best consumer, our own country. Without the relentless demand here, Colombian cocaine would disappear.
