<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet made an emergency landing at an airport today after one of its three hydraulic systems failed, an airline spokesman said. Flight 891, carrying 66 passengers and a crew of six from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, returned to <ORGANIZATION> Will </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> 11 minutes after taking off, said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. He said the loss of any one or two of the hydraulic systems would not result in the pilot losing control of the airplane, as happened with a DC-10 that crashed at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, after losing all three of its hydraulic systems. `` I want to emphasize this kind of airplane has a hydraulically assisted flight control system. But even if all three -LRB- hydraulic systems -RRB- went out ... there would be a cable system to pilot the aircraft,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said mechanics would inspect the plane, a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> MD80, to determine if it should be taken out of service and the passengers transferred to other flights.
