 Aug. 26 South Bend -LRB- Ind. -RRB- Tribune on Voyager 2: If you yawned it had to be the hour, not the event. Not since our distant ancestors emerged from the caves has humankind been treated to such sights. The marvelous journey of Voyager 2 to the edge of the solar system humbled and excited at the same time, as great human achievements have always done. The pictures of <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> and its mysterious moons may have lacked the clarity of a telecast game show, but they were vivid testimony of what man can do in his better moments. What scientists have dreamed about for decades was delivered to you on your own TV screen. ... Putting it all in perspective will take time. Drama aside, the information supplied by Voyager 2 is of enormous value in our understanding of the universe. ... The thousands of scientists and technicians involved in the Voyager expedition deserve a warm salute from those of us who sit wondering in front of the tube. As it sinks in, we can be permitted to wonder about this strange creature called man. We can reach out to the stars; we can eliminate a scourge such as polio, but tolerate war and hunger. If we can do some great things, why not others?
