 Aug. 24 The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s independence: It is billed as an effort to put an end to secrecy in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, but that is window dressing The fact is that a bill introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> would factor raw politics into the financial equations of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, creating nothing short of economic pandemonium. ... <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> and other critics complain that, like the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is autonomous. Guided by a handful of appointed experts, it moves interest rates up and down as it pleases. It is accountable to no one. Its deliberations are conducted in secret. Its decisions may not be appealed. All that is true, and let us be grateful. The alternative _ at least the alternative favored by ... <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> _ is to authorize the congressionally run <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> to audit the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s monetary transactions, which are now protected from such scrutiny, and recommend changes It is not difficult to see how this would give <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, whose impulses are unfailingly political, leverage over the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s decisions ... <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> also wants to make the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary a voting member of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, thereby enhancing <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZ