<HEAD>UNDATED: ``adjust'' it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 24 The <LOCATION> Clarksburg </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> -RRB- Exponent on the King-Leland legacies: The two black Americans achieved their measure of fame by living radically different lives One was a clergyman, the other a politician. Yet both served humanity with an identically relentless love. Today, a national holiday enshrines the transfiguring legacy of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. But it is too soon to predict whether <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will carry out the legacy of Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> in the aftermath of his tragic death in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. We are a nation that thrives on the empty grandeur of symbols. It is far more convenient to erect a graven image to the prophet than to adopt his philosophy. After King died, we named streets, buildings and schools after him. Twenty-one years later, those schools are more likely to be completely segregated. Like King, <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> believed one should live his religious convictions. Like King, he suffered an untimely death while searching for peace. Unlike many of his colleagues, <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> did not believe in traveling abroad on junkets camouflaged as `` legislative oversight missions,'' ... to luxuriate in the world's best hotels and savor the food at its most elegant restaurants. ... Instead of flying to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> ... <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> flew into <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s foggy mountainous terrain to visit dirt-poor refugee camps. But we do what <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> deplored: extolling him with words instead of exploring legislative ways to carry out his ideals. The only monuments <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> would care about would be for this nation to make a commitment to feeding the hungry, preventing the erosion of civil rights at home and seeking the sovereign dignity for all peoples abroad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 29 <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s war against legal services to the poor should have ended when he left office, but it did n't. Unfortunately, the people he chose are still running the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which passes federal funds to agencies that represent poor people in litigation. As -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has dallied in nominating people to fill the 11 seats on the <ORGANIZATION> LSC </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors, the lame ducks now in charge have continued to discredit themselves. Several months ago, the <ORGANIZATION> LSC </ORGANIZATION> hired an outside lawyer to produce a 10-page legal memorandum that argued, weakly, that the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> itself is unconstitutional. This continued the tradition of Reagan-era embarrassments, which included lucrative consulting contracts for some <ORGANIZATION> LSC </ORGANIZATION> leaders. If ... <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> longs to rekindle the extremism of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era, he could simply choose some of the 11 potential directors put forward by <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlafly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> and other fringe-dwellers. But if he backs the premise of the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ that every <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> has the right to effective legal representation ... _ he will fill those seats with outstanding Americans whose own work has shown their commitment to legal services to the poor.
