<TEXT>
 Aug. 29 The <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> -LRB- <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> -RRB- Citizen Patriot on Indian remains: <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> have a bone to pick with one of the white man's cultural institutions _ the museum Meeting in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> -LRB- N.M. -RRB- recently, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> estimated that the bones of 2.5 million of their ancestors are held in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> museums. Those remains should be returned, Indians say. Museum officials put the figures at much less. They admit to having the remains of between 100,000 and 250,000 Indians. Indeed, the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, has 18,600 Indian remains stacked in boxes in a hallway closed to the public. We do n't want to refight old wars. But here's a thought to ponder: Numbers of remains aside, if those were the bones of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> slaves, would the museums get away with this? Of course not. What, then, makes it OK to unearth the remains of Indian ancestors and `` bury'' them in display cases and boxes as an anthropological curiosity? Because `` we'' beat the red man? Because to the victor go the spoils? Sometimes we're not sure the right side won.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Aug. 26 Daily Register, <LOCATION> Portage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, on tranquilizing bears: The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> of Game and Fish encountered harsh criticism from animal rights advocates and the public in general ... after an incident in which a bear, tranquilized after climbing a utility pole, came in contact with live wires and fell to the ground. And well it should. The agency, whose primary purpose is to maintain guidelines to ensure the survival of fish and game _ including bear _ did not seem to consider this when tranquilizing the bear, which had climbed the pole after wandering into a town in search of its cub. After the bear climbed up the pole, the agency's first step should have been to cut electrical power. Next, it should have prepared for the bear's fall _ in the form of a safety net _ if the bear fell after being shot with the tranquilizer gun. Instead, the state agency did neither. The result was a 25-foot fall and contact -LRB- with -RRB- transformer coils _ in the form of 7,200 volts. The bear survived _ thankfully. A game and fish department official, after getting a host of calls criticizing the methods, said the agency was `` only concerned about the safety of residents.'' So much for its mission of ensuring the survival of fish and game.
</TEXT>
