<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reports of ties between Israelis and Colombian drug lords are overblown and only one or two companies may have violated the law, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, on a visit to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, also said there were few if any Israeli mercenaries. He and other officials sought to stem the scandal about allegations that former army officers gave paramilitary training to assassination squads for the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> drug cartel in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> media said the issue also had divided government officials and could affect lucrative arms exports to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Police questioned two more employee of Hod Hahanit, or Spearhead, a security and arms trading company said to have provided training for the cartel. <PERSON> Yair </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a reserve lieutenant colonel who heads the company, confirmed Wednesday an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official told him to leave <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> because he might be arrested _ raising the possibility the government knew more of his dealings than it has acknowledged. Parliament's law committee rejected a proposal that laws controlling the export of arms and military expertise be strengthened to allow prosecution of Israelis for offenses committed abroad. Some lawmakers said even discussing the matter could influence the current police investigation. Legislator <PERSON> Amnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> of the left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Shinui </ORGANIZATION> party said the government was moving too slowly. `` What bothers me is that, for a very long time, these things have been known,'' he said. `` In my opinion, there is no room for Israelis to be military advisers to unsavory types.'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> told journalists: `` I believe the media, especially in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, are making unjustified statements based on rumors rather than on solid information.'' He said the government was investigating and would punish any former officers who broke Israeli law. `` We are not trying to hide, to conceal,'' the defense minister said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s controls on exports of military equipment and knowledge are the most stringent in the world and companies must have <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> permits for overseas deals, <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said. `` I believe basically the number of people who have not obeyed the law ... is very, very limited,'' he said. `` One or two Israeli companies either worked without permission or went beyond the permission. Allow me also to stress the point that Israeli mercenaries are basically non-existent.'' News reports from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> said five Israelis were among foreigners involved in training killers for the drug cartels. A report in <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> papter, said defense officials ignored advice by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> two years ago not to issue permits for deals with private groups in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> because the country was unstable. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamishmar </PERSON>, another daily, said <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> was angered by Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s expression of doubt, after <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> ordered an investigation, that any <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officers had behaved improperly. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said the allegations were raising questions in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> about whether to order more Kfir jet fighters from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Arms exports usually are secret in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but the daily <ORGANIZATION> 