<HEAD>Leader Calls for Higher Living Standard at No Spiritual Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s new spiritual leader, urged the government Wednesday to raise living standards without sacrificing emphasis on spiritual goals, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported. It quoted <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> as telling President <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and his new Cabinet: `` People must n't think that. ... untangling the practical problems in the nation's life ... means moving away from the revolution's spirituality and its Islamic goals.'' <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s `` enemies'' want Iranians to believe that, if those who govern `` want to solve the problems of the people.. increase production in the country ... then probably this means forgetting, weakening or discoloring the goals of the revolution and the spiritual.'' On Tuesday, the parliament approved all 22 ministers chosen by <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, despite speculation that some technocrats would be rejected by those who wanted a more radical government. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> seeks to revive the economy and attract foreign capital to rebuild after the eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Approval of the entire Cabinet showed the parliament `` understands well the realities of the country, understands the issues and knows itself to be responsible in context of these realities and this nation,'' said <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, who was chosen as spiritual leader after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> died June 3. Missing from <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s government are such hard-liners as former Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, who is thought to have links with groups holding foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyshahri </PERSON>, the former intelligence minister and a strong opponent of restorig ties with the West. The main opposition group, the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> will have to continue purging radical elements to keep his program on track. Iranian newspapers repeated <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>'s call for economic development. `` Today is the beginning of a nationwide effort to construct and rebuild the country in a manner suitable for an Islamic society,'' said an editorial in the radical, Farsi-language <ORGANIZATION> Abrar </ORGANIZATION> daily carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. During the three-day Cabinet debate, <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> rebuffed claims that his ministers lacked political experience. He said they `` have the necessary political credentials, but this time the emphasis has been to ensure that they are also functional.'' `` Right now we have to put more effort into ensuring that the programs passed by parliament are implemented,'' he said.
