<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     08-30 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cholera Breaks Out in Squalid Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cholera has broken out at a camp housing 4,500 Vietnamese refugees who suffer from poor sanitary conditions and lack of water, a health official said Wednesday. The first case of the disease was discovered Sunday, the same day food riots hit the camp. Dr. Lo Wai-kee, principal medical officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Vietnamese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the government agency had confirmed that a 4-year-old Vietnamese boy and two women had contracted the gastrointestinal disease. He said all three, who are from different families, are in satisfactory condition. Lo said he was not surprised at the cholera outbreak at Tai A Chau, an outlying island, because of the poor health conditions there. `` The environment is not satisfactory. The potential risks are there,'' he said. He said there was insufficent water for washing, and the Vietnamese had to bathe in the sea. Garbage collection is poor, and there are no indoor bathrooms, he said. Lo said at least one of the victims had eaten improperly cooked seafood and may have caught the disease as a result. He said it was unlikely the disease was transmitted through government dry rations. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> refugee officials have said Vietnamese refugees in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s screening centers were in danger of dying because of malnutrition and disease. Lo said there was no such danger on Tai A Chau, but he acknowledged that common disease on the island include pink-eye, skin illness and enterogastritis. A medical team went to the island Wednesday and distributed drugs to the Vietnamese as a preventive measure, and the government has imposed a quarantine on the camp, he said. Lo said the restriction could be lifted in 10 days if no new cases were reported. Sunday's rioting broke out during rice distribution when about 1,000 Vietnamese started throwing stones at police. Authorities fired tear gas to disperse the stone-throwers but withdrew that night for fear of further violence. Police reoccupied Tai A Chau on Monday with helicopters and landing vessels. They found the police station, health center and public facilities destroyed and received several rape and robbery reports. By then, about 1,000 boat people had swum to a barge off the island to escape further attack. They were later moved to <PERSON> Shek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwu </PERSON> <PERSON> Chau </PERSON>, another nearby island. The government has also placed a quarantine on that island because of the cholera outbreak on Tai A Chau. On Tuesday, 13 Vietnamese were arrested on charges of rape, robbery and assault during the Sunday rioting. About 55,000 Vietnamese are staying in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, waiting for repatriation or resettlement. The government began to put newly arriving boat people on <LOCATION> Tai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> A </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chau </LOCATION> in June in an emergency measure to cope with their increasing numbers. Refugees usually stay there for about two weeks before they are inoculated and moved to other detention centers. The three cholera victims had been on the island for a month.
</TEXT>
