<HEAD>Peter Scott, Conservationist and Son of Polar Explorer, Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sir <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, a conservationist who pioneered the effort to save the world's rain forests and helped launch the World Wildlife Fund, is dead at age 79. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, a World War II naval hero and an Olympic yachtsman, died Tuesday in <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Southmead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> following a heart attack earlier in the day while visiting the western <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> city. He would have been 80 on Sept. 14. He was known internationally for his campaigns to save birds, bears, tigers and whales. In his last years he was forced to defend his father, Capt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Falcon </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, against revisionist historians who claimed the great polar explorer bungled the 1911-12 expedition in which he and four companions perished of cold and hunger. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s death was announced Wednesday by the Wildlife and Wetlands Trust, which he began in 1946 at <LOCATION> Slimbridge </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Severn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> estuary where he lived. He founded it as a haven for water birds after shooting a goose and seeing it die slowly. `` I thought I would n't do that to my worst enemy so why should I do it to a goose,'' he recalled. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> was a co-founder in 1961 of the Swiss-based World Wildlife Fund, now the World Wide Fund for Nature. He designed its panda logo and helped raise more than $ 60 million for 6,000 conservation projects in 135 countries. The fund is largely credited with saving the Indian tiger and the polar bear and with pioneering efforts to save rain forests. Buckingham Palace said <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, her husband, Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON>, and their son, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, sent condolences to <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s wid