th diamond fin. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and his family expressed anger in 1985 over a TV serial, `` The Last Place on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>,'' based on a debunking book by <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Huntford </PERSON> called `` Scott and <PERSON> Amundsen </PERSON>.'' It depicted his father as an incompetent loser and alleged that Capt. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON>, had an affair with another Norwegian explorer, <PERSON> Fridtjof </PERSON> <PERSON> Nansen </PERSON>, while her husband was battling in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION>. `` They were very friendly but I do n't believe for an instant that she had an affair with him,'' Sir <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> is survived by his two wives and three children. In 1942, he married the novelist <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, by whom he had a daughter. The marriage was dissolved in 1951 and the same year he married his secretary, <PERSON> Philippa </PERSON> <PERSON> Talbot-Ponsonby </PERSON>, who bore him a son and a daughter.
