<TEXT>
 The Israeli army is creating a special unit to help put down the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories after experimenting with soldiers specially trained in riot control, an army spokesman said Wednesday. The move marks a break with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military tradition in which troops are trained mainly as combat soldiers for conventional warfare. The new special force is intended to get regular combat troops out of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and back to standard training programs, said Col. <PERSON> Renaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON>, the army's deputy chief spokesman. <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said two experimental special companies have been operating in the occupied territories for several months. Their formation followed complaints by some officers that duty in the territories was cutting into regular training. The decision to form a permanent new unit was made after the experimental companies proved effective in dealing with Palestinians who have been waging an uprising against Israeli rule in lands occupied in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said. At least 19 Palestinians and two <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers were injured Wednesday in new clashes in the occupied territories. In the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> town of <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON>, two soldiers were injured by stones and 11 Palestinians were shot and wounded when troops opened fire during a stone-throwing melee, the army and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said. Six Palestinians were shot and wounded in three other clashes in the seaside strip. An army spokesman confirmed two Arabs wounded in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and said the military was investigating other reports. At least 554 Palestinians have been killed in clashes with soldiers or Israeli civilians during the uprising. Thirty-eight Israeli also have been slain. `` These units will spend most of their service in one place,'' <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said, adding `` they will know the area and the population better than troops that rotate in and out every three or four months.'' The special unit, dubbed the `` territories companies,'' will receive specialized training on how to deal with stone - and firebomb-throwing youths attacking troops in cities and villages, <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said He said they would operate better in such situations than elite infantry units, trained to fight regular forces on a battlefield or guerrillas attempting to infiltrate into the country. The daily <ORGANIZATION> Al-Hamishmar </ORGANIZATION> reported that new recruits are reluctant to be sent to the experimental forces, which did more police duties than the more glamorous combat units. But <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> denied the report. `` We have had no problem in recruiting men and do not expect any when we enlarge the unit,'' he said. All Israeli men do three years of compulsory military duty and serve in the reserves for up to 60 days a year until the age of 54, often in the occupied territories. Most women serve for two years in non-combat units and later in the reserves until the age of 24. <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said the possibility of hurting soldiers' morale by having them spend the majority of their three-year military service among hostile civilians had been thoroughly examined by military psychologists. `` Of course we examined the issue and we are confident the soldiers will be OK,'' he said.
