<HEAD>Public Education Weathers Censorship Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's schools are being attacked by `` self-appointed censors'' who want to ban or restrict profane or satanic books and sanitize sex education classes, an anti-censorship group said Wednesday. People For the American Way released its 7th annual report, `` Attacks on the Freedom to Learn,'' that claimed censorship and other ideological attacks on public education by religious extremists and members of right-wing organizations occurred in 42 of the 50 states. The report singled out 172 incidents that it said occurred during the 1988-89 school year, comparing them with the 157 the group reported in 1987-88. `` I want to emphasize that what is at stake in the battles being fought in communities across the nation is more than just the fate of a few novels or a textbook or two,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON>, chairman of the group founded by television producer <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lear </PERSON>. `` We are witnessing in these skirmishes the clash of two competing views of public education in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The censors see efforts to teach our children about the world around them as a threat; the rest of us see it as a way to broaden our children's vistas and opportunities. Sex education remains a major target by what the group described as the far right, which `` already scored some damaging victories'' during the last school year, the report said. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, for example, the report cited statewide restrictions that forced school textbook publishers to delete information on the use of condoms to prevent the spread of AIDS. `` There is a growing ultra-conservative movement to restrict the availability of information in the school about such topics as contraception, abortion and AIDS,'' said President <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON>, who predicted that `` attacks on sex education are likely to increase'' with recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings on reproductive rights. The report said school libraries were the target of significantly more censorship attempts during the 1988-89 school year, accounting for nearly half the challenges nationwide. It said that most of the attacks it had investigated resulted in either removal of the material or in restrictions on its use, such as requiring parental consent. `` We are finding more and more instances in which self-appointed censors focus not just on material in the curriculum but on materials available in school libraries,'' said <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON>. `` Not content with sanitizing classroom teaching, they want to scour the library shelvs of any materials of which they disapprove.'' The main targets of such challenges were literary classics such as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinbeck </PERSON>'s `` Of Mice and Men'' and <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. <PERSON> Salinger </PERSON>'s `` The Catcher in the Rye,'' as well as plays by <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Aristophanes </PERSON>, the report said. The most frequent objections, the report said, were to materials seen as containing `` offensive language'' and those perceived as touching on `` satanism, witchcraft and the occult.'' Challenges to satanism has grown over the last two years, said <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Hulsizer </PERSON>, author of the report. No challenges were reported in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakato </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the report said. It said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> led the nation with what it called 23 censorship attempts.
