<HEAD>Cracks Confirmed In Three Mile Island's Steel Lining</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A TV camera lowered into the damaged <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> reactor confirmed small cracks in a steel liner, officials said Wednesday. The cracks in the Unit 2 reactor appear to be tears in the thin stainless steel lining inside the 5-inch-thick carbon steel reactor vessel, which contains the radioactive fuel and hot water surrounding it, the plant operator said. Still unanswered is whether the cracks extend from the liner into the reactor vessel. `` There is n't any way to tell definitely, but it's not considered likely,'' said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Bedell </PERSON>, spokesman for the plant operator, <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The reactor was damaged in 1979 in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear power industry's worst accident. The investigation of the cracks required a newly developed radiation-resistant, high-resolution camera and special tools to brush debris from the area, probe the cracks and take measurements through 40 feet of water. The liner, three-sixteenths of an inch thick, prevents corrosion of the steel below it. High fuel temperatures and the difference in the contraction rates between the two types of steel caused the cracks or tears, <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear said. One crack was 6 inches long, about three-thirty-seconds of an inch wide and about one-sixteenth of an inch deep, <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear said. Three other cracks were from 3 to 5 inches long, the plant operator said. The color pictures taken Saturday revealed a few additional cracks in an area where two lines thought to be cracks were spotted in July, <ORGANIZATION> GPU </ORGANIZATION> Nuclear said. Molten uranium fuel as hot as 5,000 degrees flowed to the reactor's bottom during the March 1979 accident that damaged the reactor. A series of operator and mechanical errors cut off cooling water to the radioactive core and about half the fuel rods melted. Radioactive gas was released to the atmosphere. Since the accident, there has been no evidence that the vessel was breached, <PERSON> Bedell </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> TMI </ORGANIZATION>'s Unit 1 reactor was undamaged and remains in service. Under a program sponsored in part by the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, samples of the steel will be removed for study by researchers from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The work is expected to take up to 2 -LCB- years.
</TEXT>
