<HEAD>Educators, Doctors Join to Fight Early Youth Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Armed with evidence showing that 77 percent of the nation's adolescent deaths each year are preventable, doctors and educators joined Wednesday to form a group to attack problems confronting youth. A national commission on adolescent health was formed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The commission was formed, said <PERSON> Roseann </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON>, president of the education association, `` when we observed that we could not reduce our young people's vulnerability to AIDS, alcohol and drug addiction, heart disease and other preventable illness without changing their behavior.'' `` Hungry, sick, violated, abused, doped up kids can not learn,'' said <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON>. `` Research tells us that ` one-shot' education programs do not work, and that comprehensive multi-component programs that change behavior are critical. I can not overemphasize the need for schools, families and communities to work together. ...'' Ms. <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> will serve as commission co-chairman along with Dr. <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Others on the 31-member commission include former Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Betty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Castor </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> School Chief <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Honig </PERSON> and pollster <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallup </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendee </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> vice president for science and technology, said an estimated 77 percent of the nation's adolescent deaths each year are preventable In the 1950s, 75 percent of deaths of youths aged 10 to 19 years were due to natural causes, compared with only 27 percent in the 1980s. <PERSON> Hendee </PERSON> added that more than 75 percent of seniors who tried cigarettes first and almost 53 percent of seniors who have gotten drunk first did so before starting high school. Rates for suicide and birth for teens 10 - to 14-years-old have gone up dramatically in recent years Both the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> and education association said national attention and community based efforts should focus on comprehensive school health programs for all grades, kindergarten through 12th, and particularly on programs for the disadvantaged and those involved in risky or life-threatening behaviors.
</TEXT>
