<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Groups Claim Pivotal Victory in Florida House Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-abortion activists Wednesday claimed Republican <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>'s election to succeed late <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> proves that their movement is `` alive and well'' in the wake of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s July 3 decision on abortion. Abortion rights supporters, however, said abortion was not a key issue in the race between Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>, who had the support of abortion rights activists. During the campaign, Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, 37, a state senator, said she favored more restrictions on abortion and <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> said he favored more choice. However, with polls indicating most voters supported abortion rights, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate said abortion was more of a state legislative issue than a congressional issue. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters the organization made a $ 1,000 contribution to Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> in the Republican primary election and spent about $ 15,000 for activities on her behalf in the general election campaign. `` <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>'s win is a pivotal victory for the pro-life movement,'' Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` Clearly, the net pro-life increment is alive and well after the <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> decision.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 5-4 ruling, giving states greater power to limit abortions, appeared on the court's docket as <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> vs. Reproductive Health Services. Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON> also said that abortion was `` a highly visible issue'' in the Aug. 12 special election in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in which Republican <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, an abortion opponent, defeated Democrat <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> for the seat of former Speaker of the House <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. She said anti-abortion candidates also have won six of eight state legislative races since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision. Abortion rights leaders have contended that state legislative victories in two races in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> indicated movement in their direction in the wake of the court ruling. Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>, however, said anti-abortion candidates have won in races in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and two <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> legislative districts. <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, denied that abortion was a major issue in the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> congressional races or the legislative contests cited by Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>. `` The anti-choice movement is stretching a major point to claim victory on the issue of abortion in that -LRB- <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> -RRB- race,'' she said. `` That was not the issue.'' Republicans hailed <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>'s election as a major victory, noting that Pepper had held the seat for the Democrats since 1962 when the seat was created. Pepper died May 30 at age 88. According to unofficial returns, predominantly Latin precincts had turnouts of more than 60 percent and gave Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, the first Cuban-American elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, 80 percent to 90 percent of the vote. She carried the entire district by a 53 percent to 47 percent margin. Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>, however, said `` <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> could not have won the vote with just the Hispanic vote. There is not a majority of Hispanics in the district.'' `` There had to be other issues involved, and we feel that definitely the abortion issue played a major factor in the race,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, however, said, `` Nothing was an issue there that could supersede the ethnicity issue. The fact is that no issue, even the issue of choice, could overwhelm the ethnicity issue.'' Ms. <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON> said the abortion rights group contributed $ 5,000 to <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>'s campaign and spent about $ 2,500 on get-out-the-vote efforts.
