<HEAD>Second Shipload of PCBs Arrives in Quebec Town</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 BAIE-COMEAU, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ A second shipload of PCBs arrived at this <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> port Wednesday, the day after riot police used clubs to disperse protesters so an earlier shipment could be moved to temporary storage nearby. Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Corriveau </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Quebec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> turned down applications by a citizen coalition in <LOCATION> Baie-Comeau </LOCATION>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s hometown, for injunctions forbidding long-term storage of polychlorinated biphenals, or PCBs, from elsewhere in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>. It was the second consecutive day the coalition lost a legal battle to prevent the unloading of toxic PCBs produced in St.-Basile-le-Grand, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, and destined for a nearby <ORGANIZATION> Hydro-Quebec </ORGANIZATION> storage site. The waste was shipped to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> for destruction, but longshoremen refused to unload it. On Tuesday, shortly after refusal of the first applications, police cleareed the way to the Manic 2 storage site for six trucks loaded with PCB-laced oil. A V-formation of about 40 helmeted officers, truncheons held chest-high, pushed through dozens of noisy demonstrators so the convoy could leave the dock. Police said no one was injured and there were no arrests. The waste had been on the wharf for six days after arriving on the <PERSON> Nadezhda </PERSON> <PERSON> Obukhova </PERSON>, a Soviet freighter. Another Soviet freighter, the <PERSON> Khudozhnik </PERSON> <PERSON> Pakhomov </PERSON>, arrived Wednesday after a two-week voyage from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Provincial police tightened patrols around the dock area and closed the area to passers-by. `` It's not over yet,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a lawyer for the coalition of citizen groups. `` This is just one battle that has been lost.'' The shuttle of PCBs back and forth across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> has been seen as an embarrassment for Quebec Premier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> as the Sept. 25 provincial election approaches PCBs produce toxic byproducts such as dioxins and furans when incompletely burned.
