<HEAD>Group Says Fat-Laden Foods Barrier to Healthy School Lunches</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 7th graf, bgng, Public Voice xxx etc., to clarify that
the reference is to the 1988-89 school year.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 School lunchroom cooks are hampered in efforts to provide nutritious meals because the government donates mainly `` fat-laden foods'' such as ground beef, pork and luncheon meats, a consumer health group said Wednesday. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION>, criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the agency responsible for administering the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lunch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, for `` not providing the critical leadership necessary to speed progress in reducing fat in school lunches.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, acting administator of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, countered by saying the department is committed to dietary guidelines developed jointly with the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. He said the guidelines do n't set quantitative standards for fat. `` There is no scientific consensus on appropriate levels of fat in children's diets,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said. And the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> noted in a statement that `` children's eating habits are influenced by multiple factors such as home, school, and restaurants.'' It said parents and community groups must share responsibility for improving young people's dietary preferences. The consumer group said its survey of school food service directors shows, nevertheless, that the government school lunch program lends little encouragement to dieticians seeking to lower the fat content of lunches. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> said 67 percent of 177 school food service directors surveyed told it that the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s commodity distribution program is one of the most significant barriers to their efforts to provide nutritious meals. More than 24 million children participated in lunch programs at more than 91,000 schools during the 1988-89 academic year. The school lunch programs depend, to some extent, on commodities provided free of charge by the federal government, to help them stay afloat financially, the group said. `` Yet,'' it said, `` the commodities offered include a high proportion of fat-laden foods.'' <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> said that Agriculture Department-disbursed commodity foods account for about 30 percent of foods used for school lunches. Of the total estimated dollar value of the commodities available _ $ 817.4 million _ ground beef and pork, luncheon meat and ham, butter, cheese and eggs constituted well over 50 percent, it said. Of the `` bonus'' commodities offered to schools _ or commodities furnished above the basic allotments _ butter, cheese, pork, beef, and eggs comprised more than 90 percent of the dollar value, the group said. It said that more than 80 percent of the directors surveyed said they have taken some steps to reduce fat in their school lunches. Contrary to <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>'s statement, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> said there is a consensus among health professionals that fat in children's diets should be reduced to about 30 percent of calories. Among other findings were these: _ Only 6 percent of the directors surveyed had established target levels or ranges for fat in their programs Central city school districts were eight times more likely to establish such limits than were rural districts. _ Seventy-seven percent reported having limited access to written matrials or training programs on how to purchase foods or modify recipes to reduce fat content Twenty-three percent said they did not receive any guidance or guidelines. _ When asked to identify the single most important thing that could be done to help reduce fat, 50 percent of the respondents said the commodity program should be changed and 26 percent said more nutritional education should be provided The remaining 24 percent were uncertain. Public Voice recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> provide greater leadership in educating school food service directors and in offering assistance in planning monthly menus, including suggesting how often specific foods should be served. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also should significantly expand the availability of lower-fat commodities to the schools, the group said. Said <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>: `` It is important to remember that no matter what level is deemed appropriate, that level must be applied to a person's entire diet, not to a single food or a single meal. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> can not at this time support setting quantitative fat standards or recommended frequency of serving certain foods.'' The variety of foods donated to schools is under constant review, he said, adding that `` over the years significant progress has been made in providing more and more healthy, wholesome foods, including additional low-and reduced-fat foods.'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> also said his agency promotes and coordinates nutrition education and technical assistance for all involved in the school lunch program, although he said that states `` have great flexibility in how they spend the money they have available for training.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in its statement that young people's dietary habits are largely affected by national advertising, which it called `` a major influence on children's food preferences.'' `` If change is to become a reality, dietary modifications in school menus must be supported by parents and the community,'' it said.
