<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., unveiled on Wednesday `` debt-for-drugs'' legislation intended to offer debt-relief incentives to Latin American nations that subsidize the withdrawal of farm land from coca production The legislation, to be introduced when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reconvenes next week, is modeled on debt-for-nature exchanges already in place to help protect tropical rain forests. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> asserted in a statement that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment of $ 400 million in a debt-for-drugs plan could free up enough funds to subsidize the withdrawal of every acre in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> now in coca production. Coca crops are refined to produce cocaine, one of the principal illicit drugs on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> narcotics market. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, who is to deliver the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nationally televised adddress on drug policy next Tuesday evening, said that for the immediate future the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must continue to extradite foreign drug traffickers for trial in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. `` But in the long run, the best way to cut coca production is to provide economic incentives to grow other crops,' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., who returned this week from a 14-day visit to nine Latin American countries, contends that substituting other crops for coca will simply spread production of the enormously profitable crop to other countries <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> said the best hope is an intensive campaign to reduce narcotic consumption in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by discouraging first-time and casual users and by rehabilitating addicts. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, however, said his plan can work in the countries involved and has a `` realistic prospect of winning public support in this country.'' `` It is not a giveaway with no strings attached,'' he said. `` Americans love a good deal, and the debt-for-drugs plan is exactly that.'' Under the <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> legislation the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, hopefully with the help of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies, would create an international fund to negotiate debt-for-drugs exchanges. The fund would purchase debt owed to foreign banks by the governments of coca-producing nations. Once a sizeable amount of debt had been acquired the fund would offer to forgive a coca-producing nation's interest on it for a year in exchange for subsidies to shift farmers out of coca production. Once coca reduction targets were reached, the fund would forgive the outstanding debt in full.
</TEXT>
