<HEAD>Summary of Developments in Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the latest developments in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s war with drug traffickers:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CURFEWS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Interior Minister <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON> imposed a curfew in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> and nine other cities in cocaine country to curb violence by drug barons. The orders affect about 3 million people and give mayors broader powers to conduct searches, inspect vehicles and arrest suspects. <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON> said 100 officers had been dispatched to <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> and said military forces were ordered to intensify their crackdown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. EMBASSY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government ordered families of its embassy staff to leave <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> because of fears of attacks by drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE RESIGNATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Three more judges resigned in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> Tuesday. Since the government's offensive began, 108 judges have resigned in protest over what they feel is a lack of adequate security. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ordered the judges to resume their duties.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WEAPONS INTERCEPTED</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 National police said they intercepted a Medellin-bound arms shipment, including 169 grenades for use with a launcher, 40 fragmentation grenades and 600 firearms cartridges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE THREATS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON>, reputed leader of the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel, said the drug lords are prepared for total war if the government refuses to make peace, the French newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> said. He reportedly said drug traffickers would be willing to let the government keep all the property it has seized if narcotics chieftains were allowed to rejoin society. If the government declines, Liberation quoted him as saying, `` There will be some deaths, always more deaths.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEDELLIN MAYOR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> complained of a lack of security assistance from the national government, saying it agreed to provide an extra 100 police officers rather than the 3,000 he requested to bolster the existing force of 4,000. The mayor said his suggestion to negotiate with the traffickers had been rejected by the government, and that he was carrying out all anti-narcotics measures ordered by national authorities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ISRAEL-COLOMBIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said allegations that former army officers gave paramilitary trianing to assassination squads for Colombian drug lords are overblown. Police questioned two more employees of a security and arms trading company said to have provided training for the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel. <PERSON> Yair </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a reserve lieutenant colonel who heads the company, confirmed an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official told him to leave <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> because he might be arrested.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. AID</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 An administration source said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s drug control strategy will call for $ 250 million to $ 260 million in economic and military aid for <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>. Although <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> was the focus of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s meeting Tuesday with drug advisers, sources said no specific decisions were made on future aid to that country.
