<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has n't had any luck fishing on his summer vacation, jokingly asked a newspaper Wednesday to stop running a `` no-fish'' logo chronicling his rod-and-reel failures. The <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>'s graphic consists of a circle with a line drawn through a bluefish, similar to the `` Ghostbusters'' logo. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, whose hook has come up empty for 13 days in a row, said he planned to call the newspaper's editor. `` I think they should knock off that advertisement,'' he said during a presentation by the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> for this seaside resort and neighboring <LOCATION> Kennebunk </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pointed out that someone else on his boat had caught a fish. But Press Herald Executive Editor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said that was n't going to be enough to stop the graphic, which the paper plans to keep running as long as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s luck stays poor `` I think the president's suggestion that we credit any fish caught on his boat sounds fishy,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. `` We are eagerly awaiting his first catch of his vacation.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has until Tuesday, when he plans to head back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, to catch a fish.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bears are back. Just ask <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Klasnya </PERSON>. `` I was sitting on my back steps, going through a bag of seeds for planting, when I felt something was out there looking at me,'' said <PERSON> Klasnya </PERSON>. The `` something'' was a 200-pound black bear in her back yard relishing the aroma of pork chops frying on the stove. She ran inside, replaced the pork chops with garlic and onions to encourage the bear's departure, clapped her hands and made a fuss until the animal sauntered back into the woods. `` I'm not going to fry pork chops or bacon till the bear season is over,'' she said. Since last week's encounter, police have received more than 20 reports of bear sightings around this Lake Superior city. The bears are in town for their late-summer gorging in greater numbers than in the last two years. The influx, however, does n't come close to the invasion of 1985, when dozens of bears, searching for food here because of poor berry and nut supplies in the woods, were sighted some days. A poor crop of hazelnuts, one of bears' favorite foods, and an increased bear population, is forcing bears to move as far south as <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, experts say. Researcher <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said bears that come to <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION> looking for a meal feed on clover, apples _ and garbage.
</TEXT>
