<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international conference on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> could not produce an agreement and suspended its work Wednesday until warring factions are ready for a compromise to end a generation of violence. `` We need time so the spirit of reconciliation can overcome the spirit of confrontation, but for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> the hour of peace will come,'' <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> foreign minister, told the delegates just before adjourning the final session. Some delegates said the failure increased the likelihood of full-scale civil war when <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> withdraws its military forces Sept. 27 after nearly 11 years of occupation. Last-minute negotiations delayed a final statement by seven hours. It fell far short of the comprehensive settlement delegates from 19 nations hoped to achieve when the conference opened in late July. The statement said the meeting `` achieved progress in elaborating a wide variety of elements necessary for the reaching of a comprehensive settlement to the tragic conflict in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' but added: `` It is not yet possible to achieve a comprehensive settlement. It was therefore decided to suspend the conference.'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> offered to help mediate between the Vietnam-sponsored government of Premier <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> and the three-faction rebel alliance led by Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, who ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> until a coup in 1970. `` We will come back to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said as he left the conference hall. `` The problem is complicated. We must be patient.'' <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> told reporters the work of a fact-finding commission sent to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and other groundwork by the conference may pay off when the parties are ready to compromise. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON>, foreign minister of <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, said: `` There have been too many casualties, too much suffering, too much bitterness. ... The very fact that we can sit down together, I think this was quite a feat.'' Delegates left open the possiblity of using committees set up under conference auspices for future talks between the belligerents. According to the final statement, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> `` will begin consultations within six months with the participants in the conference with a view to reconvening the conference.'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> called the meeting when a climate of greater cooperation appeared to make settlement possible, but positions of the Cambodian factions hardened during three weeks of negotiations in small working groups. <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> said negotiations broke down on five points, including composition of a transitional government, how to monitor the withdrawal and use of the word `` genocide'' in describing <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> rule from April 1975 until <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded in December 1978. An estimated 1 million Cambodians died under the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, which now is the strongest of the three rebel factions. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> told reporters: `` We know it is the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> who have ruined the outcome of this conference, who have scuttled it.'' He said the conduct of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and its allies suggested they were preparing for civil war and `` it confirms and presages new massacres of millions of Cambodians.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration blamed <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOC