<FIRST>u a AM-PlutoniumWaste     08-30 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plutonium Waste,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Approves Stainless-Steel Waste Transport Container</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a decade of research and development culminated Wednesday in federal approval of a steel container to hold plutonium-contaminated trash during shipment to a repository in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission approved TRUPACT-2, which the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will use to haul waste to its Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a desert repository carved out of salt beds 2,150 feet below the surface of the Earth. TRUPACT-2 _ a cylindrical, stainless-steel vault-within-a-vault with 10 inches of polyurethane cushioning in between _ was designed and tested by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. It is manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Packaging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Federal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Way </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION> `` This certainly is one of the critical milestones to opening the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Tollison </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> manager of waste transportation for the plant, 26 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Carlsbad </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tollison </PERSON> said the 10-foot containers will cost about $ 200,000 each and the trailers to haul them about $ 20,000 apiece. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Neill </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a federally funded state watchdog agency, said of the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s approval, `` We're real pleased it passed muster.'' But <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear waste safety project, said the product was not adequately evaluated. The organization is a private, non-profit watchdog group. A longer evaulation `` would have included the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> reviewing the quality assurance program,'' said <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>. <PERSON> Tollison </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> had been reviewing the container program, which had its birth in the late 1970s, since 1987. TRUPACT stands for Transuranic Packaging Transporter. Transuranic wastes are those contaminated with radioactive elements heavier than uranium. The waste includes such things as gloves and tools. Each TRUPACT-2 container will hold up to 14 55-gallon drums of radioactive waste generated by the nation's weapons plants. The TRUPACT-2 containers will be carried three at a time aboard special trailers to WIPP. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the government expects to ship 600 truckloads to WIPP each year for 25 years, with the trucks watched by satellite. The desert repository has been built, but its 1988 opening was postponed because of concerns about its safety, delays in getting the land around the site withdrawn from public use and lack of certification for the TRUPACT. Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> has said the site wo n't open until he is sure all the technical concerns are resolved.
