<FIRST>r a AM-Liver     08-30 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethical Rules Say Parent Can Donate Liver to Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> have proposed that transplants in which only a piece of the liver is taken from a living donor be limited in most cases to parents supplying organs to their children. The idea, published in Thursday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, was offered for discussion in hopes the medical profession eventually will adopt such ethical guidelines. Doctors at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> drew up the rules before attempting their first transplant of a section of liver from a living donor. Transplants involving whole or partial livers taken from the dead are routine in many places. But because these organs are in scarce, some doctors would like to begin transplanting parts of organs taken from the living. Because the body has only one liver, the organ can not be entirely removed for transplant. The new surgery would remove one lobe of a healthy person's liver and transplant it into an infant. The missing part of the donor's liver eventually grows back, and in the baby, the piece of organ grows along with the child `` We believe that from the perspectives of both recipient and donor, the benefits outweigh the risks and that it is ethically appropriate to proceed with a trial of liver transplantation using a parent as a living donor,'' wrote Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> A. Singer and colleagues. The guidelines resulted from a year-long series of seminars and discussions. The doctors proposed that the donor should be the child's parent or, in rare cases, a mature sibling or grandparent. They said that when the donor is related to the recipient, the benefits of saving a life are most rewarding. Such transplants also have the best chance of succeeding. A team led by Dr. <PERSON> Christoph </PERSON> <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> surgeons hopes to perform the first such operation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this fall. The operation has already been done in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Doctors say that because of the shortage of organs from cadavers, up to half of all babies who need new livers die while awaiting transplants.
