<HEAD>Fewer Fires in Amazon This Year But Damage Still Extensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of fires set in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest has dropped from last year but the region is still suffering extensive damage, government scientists said Wednesday. They say the burning increases the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere and adds to the greenhouse effect, which causes a global warming. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said experts in the past two months detected 59,000 fires that devastated 12,700 square miles of forest _ an area larger than <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. That represents roughly 1.5 percent of the so-called legal <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION>, a 2 million-square-mile region. `` We're certainly going to have fewer fires and less destruction in 1989 than in 1988, primarily because we've had unusually heavy rains this year,'' <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone from <PERSON> Sao </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON>, 210 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>. In 1988, about 45,600 square miles were destroyed by 205,000 fires, <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> said. The institute monitors fires in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> by using satellites that detect smoke and heat. <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> said the government helped reduce the number of fires, mainly by suspending incentives for large-scale agricultural and ranching projects. It also began a plan this month to monitor part of the region by helicopter and fine those found guilty of clearing the forest illegally. Officials handed out $ 9 million in fines in the first 15 days. `` There's a greater awareness of the problem, on the part of the government and individuals, and that will make it easier to protect the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> said. Ranchers and farmers burn off large tracts of the rain forest to clear land for planting and grazing.
