<HEAD>West Germany Prepares For New Wave of East German Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials are preparing for a new wave of East German refugees seeking to flee to the West from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, but denied on Wednesday that a deal was struck to permit a wholesale exodus. Preparations went ahead to set up four tent camps in <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION> state to house an expected surge of East German refugees after Sept. 1. West German and Hungarian officials say many East German families will have to decide whether to flee to the West or return home by then because it marks the end of the school vacation in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The Stuttgarter Nachrichten newspaper said Austrian and West German rail officials worked out plans for special trains to bring refugees to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Chief government spokesman <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said the new refugee facilities are being erected `` because the government must be prepared for all possibilities. We have to take this date of Sept. 1 and the days thereafter seriously.'' West German TV quoted Hungarian Interior Minister <PERSON> Istvan </PERSON> <PERSON> Horvath </PERSON> as reiterating <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s intention not to return any East Germans against their will and again appealing to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to work to solve the problem. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said officials estimate that from 150,000 to 200,000 East Germans are on vacation in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Officials earlier speculated as many as 20,000 could decide to stay in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. West German news media reported that 15,000 East Germans would be allowed to go the West from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> by the weekend, carrying newly issued West German passports. A high-ranking government official in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, denied it and said issuing such passports would not solve the problem. `` The new passports do not have a Hungarian entry visa in them and thus could not be used to legally leave the country,'' he said. <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said news reports saying that removal of the visa requirement was imminent `` do not correspond to the facts and possibilities.'' In <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, an Austrian government source said the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> is working on a plan to ferry at least 1,500 East Germans from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in the next few days. West German officials said negotiations were continuing, but no final arrangement had been concluded. At least 6,000 East Germans are thought to have used vacations in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to flee west to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> began dismantling fortifications along the border in May. The flood of refugees has been fueled by the refusal of the communist East German leadership to adopt economic and political reforms similar to those under way in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.
