<HEAD>Bus Crash in Peru Kills 20</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two buses loaded with passengers and driven by soldiers pressed into service during a bus strike collided on an expressway, killing 20 people, police said Wednesday. More than 30 people were injured. The head-on collision occurred at 7 p.m. Tuesday about four miles from the center of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> on the main artery connecting the southern suburbs with the downtown, police said. Witnesses said the buses were packed with passengers returning home from work. Published reports Wednesday quoted witnesses who said they saw one bus swerve to avoid a child running across the road. Police had no comment on whether lack of experience on the part of the drivers figured in the accident. The buses belonged to the state-owned transportation company <LOCATION> ENATRU </LOCATION>, whose drivers struck last week demanding higher wages. Company officials said members of the armed forces were ordered in to drive the buses during the strike. The strike is one of many plaguing <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. Strikes by miners, teachers, and electrical and telephone workers recently created a state of chaos throughout the country. Many of the injured had to be taken to police and military hospitals because a three-month strike by public doctors has left many hospitals and emergency rooms unattended. Hospitals treating the casualties appealed for blood donations Tuesday night as supplies ran short due to the number and severity of the injuries. Most of the strikes are for higher wages to offset the effects of hyperinflation now ravaging <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s economy. Analysts expect inflation to pass 5,000 percent this year.
