<SECOND>AM-Lutherans,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Ends First Assembly, Passing Socially Oriented Resolutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newly merged Lutheran denomination ended its first national assembly Wednesday with resolutions on social and political concerns, including <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, striking coal miners and hunger. In addition to resolutions urging <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and backing the Appalachian miners, delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> meeting approved a measure accusing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> of abusing Palestinians. The nation's fourth-largest <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> denomination also urged participation in a `` Burger-A-Month'' campaign, in which each person gives $ 2 a month _ the approximate cost of a hamburger _ to alleviate world hunger. About 1,040, delegates representing 5.3 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Lutherans expressed special support for small rural and urban congregations on the eighth and final day of their meeting in this <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb. In a `` throwaway society'' where `` new is valued more than old and bigger is often seen as better,'' rural communities are in economic crisis and inner cities suffer `` blight, poverty'' and flight of businesses, the resolution said. The assembly called for vigorous <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to determine the fate of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisoners of war and those missing in action in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, and encouraged Lutherans to be alert to advances in science and technology. `` We must learn'' from science, said the Rev. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenning </PERSON> of Independence, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Regarding the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, the assembly said achieving peace required ending abuses against Palestinians, but also stressed security for the Jewish state and confessed past `` sinful complicity as Lutherans'' against Jews. The miners backed by the Lutherans have been on strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> since April 5. The assembly was the first since the January 1988 merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>. `` It demonstrated that it is right for us to be together. There was 100 percent enthusiasim, a marvelous identification of us as a church,'' Bishop <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, president of the denomination, told a post-meeting news conference. <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON> said the assembly's decision to join the major <PERSON> Chrisitian </PERSON> ecumenical bodies, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, were `` signs of great maturity.'' He said he was impressed by the diversity of the delegates. In addition to whites, there were blacks, Hispanics, Asian-Americans and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>. Nearly half the delegates were women. <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON> noted that the mainly white church was established with a mandate to include people of different cultures. `` We've got a long way to go, but we're on the way,'' he said. Asked about the church's budget crunch, he predicted a turnaround in congregational contributions because of the `` Mission 90'' program adopted here. `` It takes a long time to turn around a ship as big as the <ORGANIZATION> ELCA </ORGANIZATION>, but it's going to turn around,'' <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON> said. `` Mission 90,'' a new long-range program for the 1990s, emphasizes Bible teaching, evangelism, tithing and work for peace, justice, and the environment. Following one of the most heated debates of the assembly, the delegates earlier set a Sept. 1, 1991, deadline for the church pension board to sell all shares in companies doing business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Those investments are valued at $ 84.9 million. `` Seting a date to be completely divested could be a problem for the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pensions </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Chilstrom </PERSON> said. However, he said all delegates agreed that apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s racial system of government, must be dismantled. Another divisive issue was abortion. The assembly on Monday approved a resolution some interpreted as pro-choice, then reconsidered and decided to remain neutral on abortion pending a two-year study. The next assembly is in 1991.
