<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv31   08-30 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 31,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thursday Aug 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Upbeat ``Business New Year''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It looks as though there is plenty of reason for optimism heading into the traditional `` business New Year'' at Labor Day, 1989. The holiday was established 95 years ago as a national event honoring working people _ a special moment of respite from toil. But over the decades it also has evolved into a time for planning and launching new efforts toward progress and achievement, a rolling up of sleeves and getting back to work after the diversions of summer. By most accounts, the circumstances that prevail heading into the last four months of 1989 are about as favorable as they ever get in any piece of machinery as diverse and complex as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. There has n't been a recession in nearly seven years and predictions of the likely time of the next downturn have lately been pushed back again. Revised figures issued by the government this week showed the economy growing at a 2.7 percent annual rate, after adjustment for inflation, in the second quarter of the year _ up from an earlier estimate of 1.7 percent. Faced with that kind of evidence, fears have been fading fast that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s campaign to restrain inflation would result in any sort of severe business slump. The inflation-fighting mission appears, meanwhile, to have met with at least some short-term success. The consumer price index rose at a 0.2 percent annual rate in both June and July, half the pace it set over the previous five months. The producer price index of finished goods, which provides a measure of subsurface inflationary pressures, has been falling recently, as have prices of most raw commodities. There was no widespread drought this year, as there was in 1988, to put pressure on supplies and prices of farm products. World oil prices have n't made any menacing moves of late. `` Economic data released during July and August suggest that the economy is in a phase of disinflationary growth, a combination of rising growth and declining inflation that typically occurs during periods of economic recoveries,'' observed <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Vignola </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>, analysts at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Sensitive economic indicators all point to a strengthening economy.'' Along with its benefits, however, that prospect poses some problems. If the economy is going to keep chugging along, the chances would logically be reduced for a further decline in interest rates. That, in turn, would stand as a setback for many of the numerous people and businesses carrying heavy debt burdens these days, as well as for those who hoped cheaper mortgages would help them buy or sell a house. A stronger economy also would imply that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might go back to restrictive inflation-fighting after a recent period of stimulating the banking system with a shot of anti-recession medicine. Nevertheless, many analysts say, it is worth remembering that through most of the 1980s the American economy has tended to reward the optimists while punishing those who bet on bad times. `` The economy got off to a good start for the current quarter,'' stated <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Boltz </PERSON>, financial economist at the investment management firm <ORGANIZATION> T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rowe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. `` If July is any indication, the likelihood of a recession looks small this year. `` To be sure, a boom does not look in prospect either. But a soft landing followed by a slow takeoff should keep <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> policymakers satisfied.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Aug 31</NOTE>
