<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv01   08-30 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 01,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Sept. 1, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trustful Religious Settings Are Fertile Field for Crooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Trust is a basic attitude of religious people, who also stress open acceptance of strangers. These traits make them particularly vulnerable to swindlers. That's the thrust of a report by the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> and the Council of Better Business Bureaus. Based on a survey of cases from state securities agencies, the report finds `` an alarming increase in the number of investment schemes peddled to religious people.'' `` Organizers of such swindles appeal to the high level of trust often found in religious groups and communities.'' Titled `` Preying on the Faithful: The False Prophets of the Investment World,'' the report says more than 15,000 Americans have lost more than $ 450 million in such scams in the last five years. A `` growing number of investment swindlers and other sharp operators ... play on religious beliefs in order to gain the trust, confidence and life savings of the faithful,'' the report says. It details major cases in 15 states where operators, usually feigning religious motives and sometimes claiming God-endowed business talents, gained confidence of believers _ and their cash. The sharp increase in such operations `` has resulted in a surge in state-level complaints from consumers about fraud and abuse by self-proclaimed ` born again' financial planners,'' the report says. It says they often pretend to be endorsed by local or national church officials or to offer `` divinely inspired investment advice about coins, precious metals, real estate and oil and gas well programs.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, says: `` It now appears that religiously oriented swindles are one of today's hottest tickets for investment con artists. `` The problem here is not religion, but the growing number of con artists who are cynically exploiting religious faith in order to fleece unsuspecting members of the flock.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlhenny </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureaus </ORGANIZATION>, says the religious swindler feigns interest in religious beliefs `` only insofar as they can be used to run a scam.'' `` They will go to any lengths, including the exploitation of churches and deeply held religious beliefs, if they think it will work. They will take their 30 pieces of silver any way they can get them.'' <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> describes this common mode of operation: A con artist picks some religiously identifiable group, passes himself off as a member in order to put victims at ease. They, in turn, often drop their guard and fail to check out him or the so-called investment opportunity. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said the approaches usually are much the same, but the promoted investments may be almost anything. He said one outfit used Old Testament prophecy to pinpoint spots for oil wells in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Many `` con artists advertise their services in religious publications and on Christian radio stations,'' he says, while others obtain religious mailing and telephone lists and use direct mail and `` cold-call'' tactics. Some operate on a `` face-to-face basis,'' renting church basements or making appearances before church social groups, he says. These schemes `` with the personal touch'' seem to hit the elderly hardest. Whenever a religiously oriented scam starts to unravel, <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> says the con artist often claims authorities were trying to `` ruin'' or `` embarrass'' the faith or church. `` Frequently this tactic gives the con artist the time he needs to move to the next congregation,'' <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> says. This can also delay complaints to state agencies so long that his `` trail is too cold to follow.'' <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> emphasizes that the five-year estimate of more than 15,000 Americans losing more than $ 450 million includes only large-scale religious scams, each with losses exceeding $ 500,000, and not smaller swindles. Offering tips for avoiding such scams, the report lists various danger signs, including: _ Investments that seem closely tied to a particular religious belief. _ An investment promoter who tries to capitalize on status or influence in a particular religious group. _ A new member turns up with a `` sure fire'' investment scheme. _ Any investments promoted by fellow church members, since the `` most persuasive hook'' of con artists is to get `` testimony of your friends and fellow believers.'' Sometimes swindlers plead for `` Christian forgiveness'' or warn of harm to the faith if the scam is exposed, the report says, adding: `` Do n't listen to these self-serving appeals'' or be talked into `` letting an investment crook off the hook. He or she will just take the opportunity to move on to greener pastures _ and new victims.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs Sept. 1</NOTE>
