<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With AIDS appearing in many countries, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> is expanding efforts to inform missionaries about the virus and how to reduce risks of contracting it. Member denominations are being provided with educational materials, special sterilized injection kits and other resources for missionaries as they are sent to their fields. `` The risk of AIDS is real for missionaries serving in infected areas, but not very high if a person takes precautions,'' says Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frame </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NCC </ORGANIZATION> consultant on health affairs. Of 40,000 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> missionaries serving overseas, six are known to have been infected with the AIDS virus, four of them stationed in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and two in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Another missionary, a hemophiliac infected through a transfusion, died of AIDS in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, Frame says. `` The risk to missionaries is almost certainly related to profession -LRB- medical -RRB- or events that can not be predicted, such as accident or complications in pregnancy requiring blood transfusions,'' he says. `` There is also the risk of getting an injection from inadequately sterilized equipment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> has made a $ 325,000 grant to <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College-Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religion </ORGANIZATION> and to <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>'s Jewish Theological Seminary of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as part of a project to improve religious leadership among American rabbis.
