<HEAD>`Comeback' Season Brings More of Same</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is the first story in a package on the fall TV season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you did n't know better, you'd swear it was this TV season, not last year's, suffering from the creative woes of a writers strike. The 1989-90 season that officially begins Sept. 18 offers witches, nuns, inner-city teachers, cute families and buddy cops. Very little here has n't been seen before. Alarmingly, there are fewer exceptions to the rule that network fare must strive to reach new depths of mediocrity. This is n't going to help the networks stem the audience erosion that has plagued them in recent years. Who would n't rather rent a movie that be stuck with `` Baywatch?'' In seasons past, previewing the fall shows generally revealed a few that broke the same-old-stuff mold _ the `` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s Places'' and `` Miami Vices'' and `` Hill Street Blueses.'' Most of this year's new shows range from dismal to mediocre _ BUT ... <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> does have the admirable `` Life Goes On,'' a wry and realistic family drama whose cast includes a real-life Down's syndrome actor playing a teen-age son who has the condition. And CBS has `` The Famous Teddy Z,'' a sophisticated, inside-show business comedy starring <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cryer </PERSON> -LRB- `` Pretty in Pink'' -RRB- as a mail-room nobody instantly elevated to high-powered agent. It was created by <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who was owed one by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> after the network canceled his critically acclaimed `` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s Place.'' <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carsey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Werner </PERSON>, producers of the hits `` The Cosby Show,'' `` Roseanne'' and `` A Different World,'' will try to do it again with `` Chicken Soup,'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, starring stand-up comic <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> as a nice Jewish man having an affair with his <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> neighbor, played by <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON>. And CBS has `` Major Dad,'' a sitcom starring the bankable <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> McRaney </PERSON> -LRB- `` <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Simon'' -RRB- as a macho, right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> trying to adjust to married life with a liberal wife -LRB- <PERSON> Shanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> -RRB- and three step-daughters. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> could break some ground with the political crime drama `` <PERSON> Mancuso </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>,'' starring <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Loggia </PERSON> as the burned-out <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent he played in the provocative miniseries `` Favorite Son.'' And no one can accuse <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <PERSON> Doogie </PERSON> <PERSON> Howser </PERSON>, M.D.'' of copy-catting. The half-hour `` dramedy,'' from <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON> -LRB- `` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> Law,'' `` Hooperman'' -RRB- revolves around a 16-year-old boy wonder who is a physician. Otherwise, the fall lineup looks like rehashes, also-rans and sleep aids. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had little room for improvement, having already pummeled <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and CBS for four seasons. But in its effort to seek the perfect prime-time schedule it has deigned to do some minor tinkering, adding five new shows. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> added nine and eight, respectively. There's <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Sister <PERSON> Kate </PERSON>,'' starring <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON>, former glamour girl on `` Dynasty,'' who is surprisingly well-cast as a crotchety nun with a passel of precious urchins. `` <ORGANIZATION> Nutt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'' is mindless slapstick about an ill-run <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hotel, starring <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Korman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cloris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leachman </PERSON>. It comes from <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, who teamed with wunderkind <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, creator of `` Sledge Hammer!'' It is paired with `` Night Court,'' which looks like educational television by comparison. What would society do without a network hour devoted to the emotional involvements of scantily clad lifeguards? <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has met the challenge with `` Baywatch,'' sadly the only show on this season from Mr. Quality Television, Grant Tinker's company. Do you miss `` Miami Vice?'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> replaces it with another buddy-cops show. This time, it's old cop-young cop and called `` Hardball.'' Not as much style as `` Vice,'' but good character possibilities. Third-place <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, which has the greatest need for breakout shows, has settled instead for a bottom-of-the-barrel ratings ploy, `` Rescue 911,'' a graphic `` reality-based'' show about emergency calls. It is a throwback to the early days of last season when the writers strike crippled production of fiction shows and the networks had to stoop to stuff like this. This season, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> is putting it on by choice. CBS' `` Island Son'' lured perennial miniseries star <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> back to series television with a <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> locale and a role as a doctor. It was n't available for pre-season scrutiny. `` The People Next Door,'' a sitcom about a cartoonist and his family, relies on special effects and apparently hopes to capitalize on the success of `` Who Framed <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbit </PERSON>.'' It's an ambitious attempt, but does n't work. `` Wolf'' stars <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> S