<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lot of people say rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, with its wide-open spaces and small towns, is in trouble and needs a lift. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> says a modest infusion of federal funds, around $ 1.5 billion over five years, is a good place to start. The House is still working on its rural development plan. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has n't given details of what it supports, but there are hints. `` Establishing a rural development policy requires striking a balance between long-term strategies to improve rural economies and shorter term efforts to provide jobs and the infrastructure needed for long-term development and improved quality of life,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>. However, he adds, national debt `` as the predominant constraint'' on federal spending puts a lid on how much the government can spend on domestic programs, including rural development. `` But even if funding were available, it is not clear that simply adding programs or funding would be helpful in solving rural economic problems,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> says. Rural development for decades has been a goal of every administration and most office-seekers and farm organizations. Pet programs have been promoted from time to time, but the national commitment has been varied and often fuzzy. An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> task force earlier this year reported to <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> on how to improve <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s rural development efforts. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s comments about `` striking a balance'' and federal spending were included in the report. The rural economy `` has difficulty keeping pace with national economic growth,'' it said. There are fundamental problems of being a rural community: small size, isolation, an unskilled work force and a lack of institutional support. `` Cyclical recovery alone will not solve rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s problems,'' the task force said `` Without structural adjustments to enhance its productive potential, the rural economy will continue to lag, and many more rural residents will be forced to leave their hometowns.'' The task force made a number of recommendations `` within current budgetary resources and without major organizational restructuring'' to improve the effectiveness of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> rural programs. `` <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> should begin by committing itself to rural development as a major departmental mission,'' the task force said. `` <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> should articulate a clear goal for rural development and base its policy decisions on this goal. It can also take steps to strengthen its capacity for effective and concerted program action.'' Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a long-time supporter of rural development, saw the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> give unanimous approval a month ago to his Rural Partnerships Act of 1989 `` Rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today is in trouble,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. `` Compared to the nation as a whole, rural unemployment and poverty are higher and economic opportunities are deteriorating. We can not have two <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> _ one, a land of opportunity and a second, rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ left behind.'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said his bill is aimed at helping rural people, an estimated 61 million Americans, including farmers, businessmen and workers, in 14,000 small towns and cities across every state. While agriculture is important, only 10 percent of rural Americans live and work on farms. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said the problems of farmers will be addressed specifically in the 1990 farm bill and other initiatives. The Rural Partnerships Act would provide federal dollars to be matched locally to create jobs and economic opportunity through local revolving funds. Through other programs, money would be used to help improve education and health care. Safe drinking water and waste disposal would be other objectives sought by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on conservation credit and rural development, held field hearings this summer and says legislation deserves a high priority English warns, however, that significant new spending in rural communities will be impossible, given the budget crunch. But he says that if programs are targeted, modernized and used to complement each other, rural communities can be given `` a real opportunity to prosper.'' There is some feeling in the House that rural development should be dealt with in legislation to replace the 1985 farm law, contrary to <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>'s plan for keeping the two separate. Regardless of the maneuvering, there is growing evidence that rural development as an issue is around to stay. An environmental group, <LOCATION> Renew </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, said last week that `` thousands of miles of streams are polluted, pesticides continue to seep into groundwater, acid rain is changing the face of the forests, lakes and farmland, and litter is scattered over the countryside.'' In a report about `` communities at risk,'' the group said rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is changing and not for the better. <PERSON> Wes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Salina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, a non-profit research organization, said in the report's introduction that the countryside represents `` the vulnerable soft underbelly'' of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> society at large. `` The simple reality is that rural people are a dispersed minority with no political clout, marginal isolates rapidly becoming like Third World peoples,'' he said. `` And increasingly the landscapes on which they live take on a Third World appearance.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Sept. 3</NOTE>
