<FIRST>r f PM-GenericDrugs-Reax     08-30 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Generic Drugs-Reax,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Reaction From Drug Companies to Problems With Generics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Generic Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some major drug companies in effect said `` I told you so'' at the latest news of a troubled generic drug maker, but added that it was too early to tell the scope of problems among their Brand X rivals. `` You might expect that problems would eventuate,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Warner-Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Morris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. Generic drug companies do n't have `` quite the same understanding of the long-term commitment to research integrity,'' he said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is `` concerned about the recent findings because they question the reliability of some generic drugs,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Oestreicher </PERSON>, spokesman for the Nutley-based company. `` It's a serious issue.'' <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> moved Monday to withdraw from the market a popular generic high-blood pressure medicine made by <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc It was the third such action aimed at a generic company in a week, shaking the $ 5-billion-a-year industry. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is investigating 11 drug makers following allegations of fraud and corruption involving employees of the agency's generic drug section and some generic drug companies. Generic drugs duplicate brand-name products whose patents have expired, and can cost up to 70 percent less. Some major drug makers also produce generic medicines, often versions of their own drugs whose patents expired. Other research-oriented pharmaceutical companies contacted Tuesday stayed out of the fray. `` We're not in the generic business and we're going to pass on this one,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Asinari </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>. Nor would <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarsky </PERSON> comment, though she did point out that the Rahway-based company's research and development budget for 1989 was $ 750 million. `` Our response to generic competition is we will continue to discover and develop innovative medicines,'' she said. Many of the companies said it was too early too tell how widespread problems were among the generics, or whether the brand-name companies would be affected. `` I think we're all waiting holding our breath, hoping that it is n't more widespread, because ultimately in the public perception it affects the whole industry,'' <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. Analysts doubted the problems at generic drug makers would change their big brothers' strategy about entering or leaving the generic market, or make a difference to their bottom line. Analysts noted that the major profits in the research-driven drug business come from patented drugs.
