 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says he will reopen his panel's investigation of the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, expected to require the government's largest-ever thrift rescue. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, branded the collapse of the thrift based in <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a `` mini-Watergate.'' He said his committee had suspended its probe only because of the pressing need to pass emergency legislation bailing out the savings and loan industry. Now that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has passed the bill, <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> vowed to clear up the scandal `` once and for all.'' Previously <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> has criticized <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thrift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION>, for delaying regulatory action against <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> and allowing the thrift's losses to balloon. The probe is sure to examine political contributions from <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the chairman of <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s parent firm, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, to five senators who later met with regulators about <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>. They are Sens. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif.; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATI