<HEAD>Regulators Urge Quick Decision on Selling Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has urged a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> utility to decide soon whether to sell or dismantle its <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear power plant, which voters said last June should close. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murley </PERSON>, director of the commission's office of nuclear reactor regulation, told officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that uncertainty about the fate of the 913-megawatt plant was making it difficult to plan regulatory changes there. `` It does make it awkward to keep carrying these options for a long period of time,'' <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> told the officials in a meeting at <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. The unusual circumstances of the plant's forced shutdown has put it in `` uncharted waters,'' he said. Other commission staff members noted, for example, that they may need to know the plant's fate before deciding whether to approve the utility's plan for reducing its emergency staff or its request to be exempted from an on-site emergency exercise. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> must approve any transfer of the utility district's nuclear license to another operator, but it also must approve the various regulatory adjustments required in the event the plant is decommissioned and eventually dismantled <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>, general manager of the utility district, assured <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> and other commission staff members that the question of whether to sell <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seco </ORGANIZATION> would be resolved `` very soon.'' <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said efforts to sell the 15-year-old plant probably will be abandoned if no agreement is reached by Friday with <ORGANIZATION> Quadrex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` I do not see anyone else coming forward ... to continue this process,'' of negotiating to buy the plant, <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said, adding later that he was `` cautiously optimistic'' that a deal could be worked out this week with <ORGANIZATION> Quadrex </ORGANIZATION>. The Rancho Seco station has been shut down since June 7, the day after utility district residents voted against keeping the plant running. It was the first time an operating nuclear power plant was closed by voter initiative. The vote did not explicitly prohibit the utility from selling the plant, and a buyer such as <ORGANIZATION> Quadrex </ORGANIZATION> could be allowed to run it if the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> approves a license transfer. Under such circumstances, <ORGANIZATION> Quadrex </ORGANIZATION> would have to restart the reactor. If a deal is struck with <ORGANIZATION> Quadrex </ORGANIZATION>, and arrangements are set for the utility to buy back some of the power generated by <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, then the district's board of directors would vote on it Sept. 7, <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> said. Any proposed sale would be put to a public vote, tentatively scheduled for Dec. 12. <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> and other officials of the utility also told the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> they were offering key workers special severance agreements in order to keep them from quitting. Licensed operators, for example, are being assured they will get the equivalent of six months salary in the event they are laid off _ money they would n't get if they resigned.
