<HEAD>GAO Report Backs Checchi Claim About Northwest Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' new owners should be able to repay the carrier's $ 3.1 billion debt with cash from its operations, including income from sale-leaseback arrangements on aircraft, congressional auditors say. Through 1993, the airline will have at least $ 635 million a year left over after servicing its debt and paying taxes, according to an analysis by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, prepared the report for the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aviation subcommittee, Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>., who planned a hearing this fall on the sale of the airline's parent company, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to a group led by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> The leveraged buyout will give <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> one of the highest debt loads in the industry, and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> is investigating the sale to determine whether it will compromise the carrier's safety. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, who could ground the <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, - based airline if he believes it is unsafe, is expected to finish his investigation next month <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> filed documents with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> saying he expects to repay the carrier's debt through cash flow from its operations. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said its analysis shows the claim `` appears to be true.'' For 1989, the airline would have $ 1.8 billion in cash available, including $ 364 million in income from operations and $ 834 million from selling aircraft and then leasing them back. After servicing debt, paying taxes and meeting other expenses, the airline would have $ 166 million left over, according to the report. By 1993, the company is projected to have income of $ 2.1 billion, including $ 570 million in revenue from the sale-leaseback arrangements. After debt payments and other expenses the airline would have excess cash of $ 635 million, according to the report. The airline could cover any cash shortfalls by selling Japanese real estate it owns or drawing on a $ 250 million line of credit, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The report confirms what the airline has been saying about the buyout in public statements and government filings, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON>, a spokesman for the carrier, said Tuesday. `` We're committed to continuing to grow the airline, to continue making it more and more competitive and to handle the debt load brought on by the purchase in a prudent business manner,'' <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> said. However, the new debt `` weakens <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s financial ratios and creates lower income due to higher interest payments,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said.
