<HEAD>Heat Brings Early Harvest, Predictions Of Great Wines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORDEAUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The grape harvest in the <LOCATION> Bordeaux </LOCATION> wine region has begun several weeks earlier than usual because of hot, dry weather, and growers predict an exceptionally good vintage. <PERSON> Jean-Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Delmas </PERSON>, director of Chateau Haut-Brion, said picking of grapes destined for white wines began Tuesday in his vineyards, with the red wine harvest likely to start later in the week. `` I can assure you, at least if it does n't rain, that the 1989 vintage will be the greatest in the century,'' <PERSON> Delmas </PERSON> said. He said it was the first time since 1893 that the harvest has opened before Sept. 1 at Chateau Haut-Brion. Because conditions can differ markedly even between nearby vineyards, the harvest starts at varying times. The hot and dry conditions that lead to early harvest give the grapes an unusually high sugar level. They are likely to produce a comparatively small amount of wine but of very high quality, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Interprofessional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of the Wines of <LOCATION> Bordeaux </LOCATION>.
