 <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that it will take $ 100 million less than the expected $ 1.225 billion for its psychiatric company, the largest <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> unit for sale to help finance the company's management-led takeover. <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> executives said in March, when shareholders voted to sell the company for $ 3.6 billion, that subsidiaries would be sold to repay a $ 1.3 billion bridge loan due in two years. `` We are ahead of schedule of our repayment of the bridge loan,'' <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> said. The company said in a news release that it has received senior loan financing commitments and other financing details involved in selling <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. Psychiatric company executives and an employee stock ownership plan support the sale. While <ORGANIZATION> HCA </ORGANIZATION> will accept the lower purchase price, it will retain ownership of $ 150 million in the psychiatric company's common stock and preferred stock along with warrants to buy additional shares of common stock. Officials said $ 650 million in financing will be provided by <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> also will buy $ 60 million of the psychiatric company's senior discount notes. <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <OR