<HEAD>IBM Japan, Toshiba to Establish Color LCD Manufacturing Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday they plan to establish a joint venture company to make color liquid crystal displays _ key components in popular computer terminal screens. Plant construction for the new company, called <ORGANIZATION> Display </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, will begin in March 1990 in <LOCATION> Himeji </LOCATION>, about 375 miles west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, with completion scheduled in April 1991, the companies said. The equally owned <ORGANIZATION> Display </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>, with an initial capital of 1 billion yen, or about $ 7 million, will have an annual production capability of 1 million 10-inch or larger LCDs by 1994, said <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> managing director <PERSON> Tsuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawanishi </PERSON> at a joint news conference. LCDs are among the most important technologies for future products for both <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, the companies said. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> managing director, <PERSON> Nobuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mii </PERSON>, said color LCDs made be Display Technologies would be sold to the parent companies. He said <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s second-largest electric machinery maker, and <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> would incorporate these devices in their products, including personal computers and work stations, for marketing worldwide.
