<HEAD>Exxon Appoints Environmentalist To Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it has named marine scientist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> as a director, in response to shareholder demands for the addition of an environmental expert following the nation's worst oil spill. <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, 62, is president and a senior scientist at Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution. He also will serve on the board's newly formed public issues committee, which will monitor the company's environmental policies `` This is a good day for the environment and <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' said <PERSON> Comptroller </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON>, trustee for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s employee, firefighter and police pension funds. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was one of several pension funds with large holdings of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> stock that has publicized its dissatisfaction with the oil giant's handling of the March 24 spill and cleanup effort. The funds, which included <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Public Employee Retirement System, the largest individual <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> public pension fund, had called for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to appoint a director with expertise and interest in the environment. <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> said the appointment `` demonstrates environmental and social responsibility'' in the aftermath of the disaster in which the tanker Exxon Valdez hit a charted reef and spewed millions of gallons of oil into Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. In a telephone interview from his office in <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, about 70 miles south of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on the southeast end of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> spoke of the spill. `` I think it's a terrible tragedy and a major disaster not just for the animals but for the people in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> said. He declined to comment on <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s handling of the cleanup but said he would visit <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in about two weeks for a separate scientific meeting on arctic research and would view the remnants of the spill at that time. `` It will give me an opportunity to discuss these research and scientific questions with colleagues in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> will serve on the board until <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s annual shareholder's meeting next April, when his name will be submitted for shareholder approval along with the other directors, said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> At the company's annual shareholders last May, shareholders demanded changes in what they called <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s `` inadequate state of preparedness'' for dealing with future problems. Although the funds ultimately voted for management this year, they warned of a major shareholder revolt next year if the Exxon appointment was unsatisfactory to dissident shareholders. At the May meeting, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> management agreed to create the six-member public issues committee, which includes four non-Exxon employees. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said the committee would review the corporation's `` policies, programs and practices on public issues of significance including their effects on the environment and worker safety and health. <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>'s appointment increases the size of the Exxon board to 15, including ten non-employee directors. Born in <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>'s career includes 26 years at the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. He joined Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution in 1977. <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>'s principal research includes the marine environment. He is the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for Exploration of the Sea.
