<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose sharply Wednesday against key foreign currencies after a mixed performance overseas. Gold prices slipped. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 361.80 a troy ounce, down $ 1.80 from late Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid for gold of $ 360.35 an ounce, down $ 1.65. Currency dealers said market sentiment toward the dollar was bullish following the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government reports showing continued economic strength, which lessens the possibility of lower interest rates. `` The economic numbers ... continued to keep the dollar well supported in spite of technical selling,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holzer </PERSON>, chief currency dealer for <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The government reported Wednesday that personal incomes rose a brisk 0.7 percent in July while consumer spending climbed at the fastest rate since April. On Tuesday, the government revised upward its estimate of total economic growth, putting the increase in the gross national product during the second quarter at a healthy 2.7 percent annual rate instead of the anemic 1.7 percent rate reported a month ago. Dealers say they're now awaiting a report on August unemployment due out Friday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 1.07 Japanese yen to a closing 143.08 yen. It was quoted higher in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 143.33 yen, and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 144.25 yen, up from 143.01 late Tuesday. The dollar rose against the British pound. It cost $ 1.5815 to buy one pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, cheaper than $ 1.5945 late Tuesday. Sterling fetched $ 1.5779 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.5870. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday, included: 1.9533 West German marks, up from 1.9362; 1.6832 Swiss francs, up from 1.6704; 6.5775 French francs, up from 6.5285; 1.1769 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1754; and 1,400.50 Italian lire, up from 1,391.25. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday, included: 1.9465 West German marks, up from 1.9375; 1.6770 Swiss francs, up from 1.6685; 6.5515 French francs, up from 6.5325; 2.1830 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1940; 1.1760 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1724; and 1,389.50 Italian lire, down from 1,396.00. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 360.75 an ounce from Tuesday's $ 364.00. But it closed higher in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, at $ 361.80 an ounce from $ 360.75. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.55 to close at a bid $ 362.37 an ounce. Silver prices declined. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver for current delivery fell to $ 5.085 a troy ounce from $ 5.091 late Tuesday. Silver fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 5.11 an ounce from $ 5.15.
