<HEAD>Arby's Owner Spurns Franchisees' $200 Million Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of franchisees operating more than 500 <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION>'s fast-food restaurants said Wednesday it had offered over $ 200 million for the chain, but the owner says it's not interested in selling. <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is owned by a company controlled by <ORGANIZATION> DWG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Miami-based holding company controlled by industrialist <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>. The group of eight franchisees said it wanted to buy the Atlanta-based chain because <ORGANIZATION> DWG </ORGANIZATION>'s continued ownership could threaten the stability of <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, partly because of <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>'s legal and financial problems. `` We believe strongly that <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> should be owned by its franchisees,'' the group, incorporated as R.B. <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said in a letter Tuesday to fellow franchisees. `` We are not trying to profit from taking the lead here,'' said the letter, released Wednesday. `` We are trying to protect the Arby's system.'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> pleaded no contest in 1987 to federal income tax evasion and was sentenced last year to five years probation on the condition that he pay all his back taxes, penalties and interest, the cost of prosecuting his case and create a $ 3 million fund to benefit the homeless. `` We think it is very unlikely that <PERSON> Arby </PERSON>'s could remain unaffected by all these pressures on Mr. <PERSON> Posner </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> DWG </ORGANIZATION>,'' read the franchisees' letter. <PERSON> Arby </PERSON>'s is a wholly owned subsidiary of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Beach-based <ORGANIZATION> Chesapeake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, of which <ORGANIZATION> DWG </ORGANIZATION> is a 60 percent owner. <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>, in a statement released Wednesday, termed the R.B. Partners proposal `` an unsolicited purported offer.'' <PERSON> Chesapeake </PERSON> also said, `` as it had previously informed such franchisees, it presently had no interest in pursuing such a sale.'' <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, who is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is `` committed to the continued growth and expansion of <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION>'s _ a process which, under his management, had resulted in outstanding performance and growth since its acquisition in June 1984,'' <PERSON> Chesapeake </PERSON> stated. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> could not be reached for comment Wednesday. A secretary said President and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was in a meeting. The franchisees said their offer represents three times what <ORGANIZATION> DWG </ORGANIZATION> paid for the chain in 1984 as part of its acquisition of Royal Crown Cola Companies. <ORGANIZATION> Arby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, with about 2,100 restaurants, reported total revenue of $ 153.8 million and an operating profit of $ 20.7 million in 1988. A spokesman for the franchisees, who asked that his name not be used, said Wednesday the group wass confident it could raise the money for the deal and had been assured by a number of institutions that it could get financing. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, a restaurant industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said there have been some cases of successful franchisee buyouts. But he said the main obstacle for the group would be raising the money. `` I do n't believe there would be any legal hurdles. You have to come up with the money,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said.
