<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise as Demand for Heating Oil Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Increased demand for home heating oil helped boost prices for energy futures across the board Wednesday. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the September contract for heating oil rose 0.94 cent to close at 53.11 cents a gallon after rising 0.45 cent on Tuesday. Demand for heating oil surged after an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> supply report issued late Tuesday indicated that inventories of the fuel did not increase as expected, said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Wholesale unleaded gasoline futures also rose, continuing the momentum begun in Tuesday's session Gasoline for September delivery picked up 0.39 cent to close at 55.00 cents a gallon, adding to a 0.96 cent advance Tuesday. `` The rising -LRB- refined -RRB- products market helped to bring crude up,'' <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON> said. More crude oil is needed when demand for heating oil and gasoline increases. The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 19 cents to settle at $ 18.83 a barrel after having closed unchanged on Tuesday.
