<FIRST>u f AM-Kellogg-Cholesterol     08-30 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kellogg-Cholesterol,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kellogg Introduces New Cereal It Claims Lowers Cholesterol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, trying to take advantage of consumers' increasing concerns about health, on Wednesday entered the growing market for foods that purportedly lower cholesterol. <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> at a news conference unveiled a new cereal, Heartwise, which contains oat bran and psyllium. The two grains are high in soluble fiber, which is believed to help the body rid itself of cholesterol. High levels of cholesterol have been shown to increase the risk of heart disease. In introducing its new product, which is expected to reach stores in the fall, <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> is challenging one of its biggest competitors, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, whose Benefit cereal contains the same ingredients. <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> said it would spend $ 40 million in the first year to advertise and promote the new cereal. It will be marketed nationwide. A variety of oat bran products have exploded onto the market since researchers said the grain could help reduce cholesterol levels. But psyllium, a grain grown mainly in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, is a relative newcomer in terms of foods connected with healthy hearts, although it has been used for years in laxatives such as <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s Metamucil. The outer husk of psyllium contains soluble fiber that has been shown to reduce cholesterol, the cereal makers claim. General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>' promotion of Benefit has been challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, which was ordered by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to refrain from advertising health claims for Metamucil. <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> contends psyllium is a drug and should be regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>. However, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, instead of declaring psyllium a drug _ and thereby forcing companies to undergo lengthy approval procedures _ is developing a regulation governing health claims on product labels including foods such as cereal. Other cereals made by <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, include Corn Flakes and <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> <PERSON> Krispies </PERSON>. Heartwise will be targeted to consumers age 35 and older, but <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> is planning an advertising campaign that promotes the cereal's benefits for children as well as adults.
