<HEAD>Copper Futures Rebound on New Strike Concerns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to change to October WTI quote, sted September.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices rebounded Wednesday on news of a strike vote by workers at a <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> mine, but gains were tempered by reports that labor troubles elsewhere may be easing. On other futures markets, frozen pork belly prices remained strong; cattle and hog prices were mostly lower; wheat futures fell; corn and soybeans were mixed; precious metals declined; and oil futures rallied. In trading at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, copper settled 1 cent to 1.85 cents higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 1.29 a pound. The market's strong tone came from reports that workers at Chilean Copper's <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> mine voted to strike on Sept. 1, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, a metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Although labor and management were continuing to talk after Tuesday's vote, copper prices `` closed firm over that strike uncertainty,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. Still, the market failed to regain the strength it had shown before Tuesday's collapse, when prices settled at least 7 cents lower. The settlement price Wednesday of the September contract was just a penny higher than Tuesday's. Weakness stems from a feeling among traders that settlements may be near in walkouts at <ORGANIZATION> Highland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> mine in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. `` Most people are feeling that the supply thinness emanating from the special situations is easing,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. Gold and silver prices declined in mostly featureless trading at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Pressure on both metals came from the strength of the dollar, analysts said. Gold selling also was encouraged by concerns that Tuesday's gains `` were somewhat overdone,'' <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said. Gold prices settled $ 1.50 to $ 1.80 lower, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 361.80 a troy ounce; silver settled .8 cent to 1 cent lower, with the September contract at $ 5.085 a troy ounce. Pork belly prices held strong in trading at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where cattle and hog futures were mostly lower. The bellies' strength was tied to rumors of possible export sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pork to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, while gains were tempered by a lack of strong market fundamentals. Supplies remain abundant, and there's been no sign that lobbying by pork producers has persuaded the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to include pork in `` in whatever charity package we're going to be sending to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, a livestock consultant in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> DEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We bought the rumor ... we have n't necessarily sold the fact,'' he said. `` The market wants to see something in writing. The ball definitely rests in the adminstration's hands.'' Live cattle settled .20 cent to 1.05 cents lower with the contract for delivery in September at 72.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent lower to .05 cent higher, with September at 82.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .90 cent lower to .15 cent higher, with October at 40.77 cents a pound; and pork bellies settled .05 cent lower to .65 cent higher, with February at 43.17 cents a pound. Wheat futures dipped while corn and soybeans were mixed in trading at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Weather concerns kept a lid on prices, as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-day forecast does not include a chance for an early frost and calls instead for nrmal rain and temperatures in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. In addition, more rain is expected to move into the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> by the end of the week, adding further downward pressure to prices, analysts said. Wheat settled 2 -LCB- cents lower to 1 \ cents higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.85 -RCB- a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to -RCB- cent higher, with September at $ 2.31 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 2 -LCB- cents lower, with September at $ 1.32 -LCB- a bushel; and soybeans settled 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher, with September at $ 5.79 \ a Oil and gasoline futures climbed at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Crude oil settled 19 cents to 31 cents higher, with the contract for delivery in October up 19 cents at $ 18.83 a barrel; heating oil was .81 cent to 1.03 cents higher, with September at 53.11 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline settled .39 cent to .62 cents a gallon, with September at 55 cents a gallon.
