<SECOND>BC-Stock Baskets,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Amends Proposal for Stock Baskets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, facing a ban on `` stock basket'' trading, announced Wednesday it filed documents to clarify that the investments are securities, not futures contracts. The amended proposal filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was in response to an Aug. 18 decision by the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, which halted trading in stock baskets, investments based on the value of broad market indexes. The court said the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> erred last May in approving stock baskets, also known as cash index participation shares, because they do not fall under the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s jurisdiction. The court classified the investments not as stocks but as futures contracts, which fall under the jurisdiction of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> have traded stock baskets for several months. According to a news release from the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchange, the new filing contains proposals that will allow investors who buy or sell stock baskets to sell their shares at any time without any penalty. Previously, investors were charged a penalty unless the sales came at the end of a quarter. Also under the new filing, those investors selling the instruments will receive a price that reflects the value of the underlying stocks at the opening of the market that day, rather than at the previous day's close. `` These changes are in line with the ruling of the <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and should remove once and for all the obstacles that stand before us,'' said <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>, the exchange's president. The <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchange first sought <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> approval for stock baskets in March 1988. Baskets are priced to reflect changes in indexes such as the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks. Investors receive quarterly cash payments equal to a proportionate share of any regular cash dividends declared on the stocks in the index.
</TEXT>
