<HEAD>Jake Butcher, Wilson, Hit With New Fraud Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> gubernatorial nominee <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON>, already serving 20 years in prison for bank fraud, was hit Wednesday with a new federal indictment accusing him of receiving illegal bank loans. Indicted along with <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON> was his one-time partner, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, currently serving a 10-year bank fraud term, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Harriette </PERSON>, and nine other people. `` We feel the alleged criminal acts represent utter contempt for the criminal justice system,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Genzman </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Named as an unindicted co-conspirator was <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Justice </PERSON>, the imprisoned former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orlando </ORGANIZATION>, which went out of business in 1986. <PERSON> Genzman </PERSON> called the case `` round three of a continuing investigation into the collapse of the bank.'' The 51-count indictment accuses the defendants of involvement in a scheme to obtain $ 3.5 million from `` nominee borrowers'' for Butcher and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> after they had declared bankruptcy in 1984 and 1985. They were also facing a federal fraud investigation in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> relating to the collapse of their banking empire. Justice allegedly accepted $ 75,000 in kickbacks to arrange the loans from <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The loans were nominally for other bank clients, but were actually delivered to Butcher and the <ORGANIZATION> Wilsons </ORGANIZATION>, according to the indictment. The indictment includes counts of making false statements on loan applications, bank fraud, conspiracy to commit bank fraud and misapplication of funds. <PERSON> Genzman </PERSON> said prosecutors anticipate having all the defendants present for arraignment within 12 days. Butcher could face a maximum 71 years in prison and fines of $ 4.5 million on the charges, while <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> faces 126 years and $ 8 million in fines. Mrs. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Longwood </LOCATION>, could be sentenced to 57 years and a fine of $ 3.5 million. Also indicted were <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> L. `` Red Dog'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogle </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Altamonte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Streck </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gresham </PERSON> and his girlfriend <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chitwood </PERSON>, both also of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Artrip </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Longwood </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Cookeville </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tenn </PERSON>.
