<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Merger     08-30 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Merger,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Admits Urging Clients to Buy Stock During Merger Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of two Japanese banks planning a major merger admitted Wednesday it had urged its clients to buy stock in the bank in June, but said this had no connection with the merger talks then under way. `` It was intended to increase the number of stable shareholders of the bank's stock,'' said <PERSON> Fukio </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, the seventh-largest bank in both <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the world, and <PERSON> Taiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobe </PERSON>, the eighth-largest, announced Tuesday they will merge April 1 to meet intensifying competition from domestic and foreign banks. The new bank will be the world's second largest. Wednesday's disclosure triggered criticism that <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was using insider information for its own advantage, but <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON> said the stock campaign `` had no connection with the merger talks.'' <PERSON> Taiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobe </PERSON> has been seen as the main beneficiary of the merger in terms of its stock price. <PERSON> Taiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobe </PERSON> stock had been steady at the equivalent of about $ 9.80 a share until late June, when it began rising. It closed at $ 11.40 Monday, the day before the merger was announced. Trading in both banks' stock was suspended Tuesday to give investors time to digest details of the merger plan. On Wednesday, buy orders in anticipation of further rises in <LOCATION> Taiyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>'s stock amounted to 64 million shares, while 450,000 shares were offered for sale. The stock closed Wednesday at $ 13.50 after the maximum one-day gain of $ 2.10 allowed under stock exchange rules. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>