<HEAD>Pickens Says He Won't Run For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA WEISGERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oilman and corporate raider <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said Wednesday he will not run for governor in 1990, but left open his options for 1994. The 61-year-old <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said the crush of his business would not allow him to commit 100 percent of his time to the needs of the state. `` It's not the time,'' he told about 500 people at a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rotary </LOCATION> luncheon, ending weeks of speculation. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said he had prepared two versions of his speech _ one announcing his candidacy and the one he delivered. He and his wife, <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON>, reached their decision late Tuesday at their hotel room in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said, and were still discussing it Wednesday morning. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> did not rule out a run in 1994. `` That's an option,'' he said. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> would not endorse any of the Republican candidates who would have been his rivals in the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primary. His decision not to run, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said, was based on his involvement in his <ORGANIZATION> Mesa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> and his <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shareholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, an oil and gas firm, lost $ 13.4 million in the second quarter and will likely post a loss in the third quarter, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said, refusing to speculate on how large the loss might be. He blamed the losses on declining natural gas prices. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>, once feared as a corporate raider and who made a $ 518 million pretax profit in a 1983 attempted takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said it was the first loss for the company in 16 years. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> also said he plans to continue his efforts to open up opportunities for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and may `` significantly'' increase his stake in <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese auto parts supplier. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Boone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> owns 20.2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION>. Although <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> is <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder, he has been denied a seat on the company's board. He said he plans to call for a special <ORGANIZATION> Koito </ORGANIZATION> shareholders meeting in coming weeks and will continue to work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade officials to `` level the playing field'' in trade and investment with the Japanese. `` I think the Japanese are just not playing a fair game,'' he said.
